and]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Scotland]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Wales]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/coronavirus-covid-19/ Coronavirus (COVID-19) on the NHS website]\n* [https://www.gov.uk/coronavirus Coronavirus (COVID-19): UK government information ]\n* [https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2020/129/contents/made The Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]. Legislation.gov.uk\n* [https://www.publichealth.hscni.net/publications/advice-covid-19-coronavirus Public Health Agency] \u2013 Advice on COVID-19 (coronavirus)\n* [https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/uk/ Worldometer UK Statistics] \u2013 Worldometer graphs and statistics for the UK\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Portal bar|United Kingdom|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Woofboy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly April 2020", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "Carole Baskin", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American animal rights activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Carole Baskin\n| image              = Carole Baskin September 2019.png\n| alt                = Carole Baskin looks to her right side\n| caption            = Baskin in 2019\n| other_names        = {{hlist|Carole Stairs Jones|Carole Murdock|Carole Lewis}}\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1961|06|06}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar County]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|[[Animal sanctuary]] executive|animal rights activist}}\n| known_for          = ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness|Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness<nowiki/>]]''\n| spouse             = {{Plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Michael Murdock|1979|end=div.}}\n* {{marriage|Don Lewis|1991|2002|end=[[Legal death|legally dead]]}}\n* {{marriage|Howard Baskin|2004}}}}\n| children           = 1}}\n'''Carole Baskin''' (''[[Given name#Name at birth|n\u00e9e]]'' '''Carole Stairs Jones'''; born June 6, 1961) is an American animal rights activist and owner of [[Big Cat Rescue]], a non-profit animal sanctuary based near [[Tampa, Florida]]. Baskin drew public attention for her role in a 2020 [[Netflix]] true crime documentary limited series, ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', a series about the life-to-date of private zoo operator [[Joe Exotic]]. The Netflix series follows both Baskin and Joe Exotic, filming their ongoing and escalating feuds over [[Exotic pet|exotic animals]] in [[Zoo|private zoos]].\n\n==Early life==\nCarole was born on June 6, 1961 on the [[Lackland Air Force Base]], in [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar County]], [[Texas]], United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s1Gnw7SmYTQ|title=1961 06 06|author=Carole Baskin|date=February 26, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> At age nine, Baskin expressed an interest in saving cats but decided against pursuing a career in [[veterinarian|veterinary medicine]] after she learned that they [[Euthanasia|euthanize]] animals.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/> Baskin [[Dropping out|dropped out]] of high school and left her home at age fifteen with a local [[roller rink]] employee.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/><ref name=\"Intel\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/joe-exotic-and-his-american-animals.html|title= Joe Exotic bred lions, tigers, and ligers at his roadside zoo. He was a modern Barnum who found an equally extraordinary nemesis.|author=Robert Moor|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Intelligencer]]}}</ref> Baskin hitchhiked back-and-forth between Florida and [[Bangor, Maine|Bangor]], [[Maine]] where she would sleep under parked cars.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> Baskin later purchased an orange [[Datsun]] truck and slept in the back with her pet cat.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> Baskin returned to Florida and worked at a department store where she began a relationship with her boss Michael Murdock.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> At age seventeen, Baskin moved in with Murdock, got married, and had a daughter.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> To make money, Baskin began [[Animal breeding|breeding]] show cats.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> Baskin also began rescuing [[bobcat]]s and using [[llama]]s for a [[Lawn mower|lawn trimming]] business.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/><ref name=\"Intel\"/> Baskin later became involved in the [[real estate]] business with her second husband Don Lewis.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/>\n\n==Career==\nBaskin and her then-husband Don Lewis founded [[Big Cat Rescue]], an [[animal sanctuary]] near [[Tampa, Florida]] for [[big cat]]s, in 1992. Baskin is the current chief executive officer of Big Cat Rescue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2020-03-17/netflix-doc-who-is-carole-baskin/|title=Who is Carole Baskin? Meet the real life activist from Netflix's Tiger King|website=Radio Times}}</ref><ref name= people>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/kim-kardashian-praises-netflix-tiger-king/|title=Kim Kardashian Praises Tiger King \u2014 and Wonders if Carole Baskin Could Have Killed Her Husband|website=PEOPLE.com|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325012204/https://people.com/tv/kim-kardashian-praises-netflix-tiger-king/|archive-date=2020-03-25|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin/|title=Carole Baskin|date=March 22, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117123404/https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin/|archive-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Baskin has used social media such as [[Facebook]] and [[YouTube]] and her \"The Cat Chat\" podcast to promote her big cats activism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vengreso.com/blog/big-cat-rescue-carole-baskin|title=Big Cat Rescue\u2019s Carole Baskin|date=May 17, 2014|accessdate=March 31, 2020|author=Bernie Borges}}</ref> In March 2020, Big Cat Rescue temporarily closed to the public due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Florida|coronavirus pandemic in Florida]].<ref name=\"esquire\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a31903483/tiger-king-carole-baskin-now-alive-big-cat-rescue/|title=Carole Baskin started a Nearly Lethal Feud in 'Tiger King.' Here\u2019s Where She Is Now.|first=Gabrielle|last=Bruney|date=March 23, 2020|website=Esquire|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325192139/https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a31903483/tiger-king-carole-baskin-now-alive-big-cat-rescue/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://decider.com/2020/03/24/tiger-king-carole-baskin-where-is-she-now/|title=Who Is Carole Baskin in \u2018Tiger King\u2019 and Where Is She Now?|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325130438/https://decider.com/2020/03/24/tiger-king-carole-baskin-where-is-she-now/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Marriages===\n[[File:Tiger at Big Cat Rescue.jpg|thumb|right|A tiger at Baskin's animal sanctuary [[Big Cat Rescue]], pictured in 2012.]]\nAt age seventeen, Baskin moved in with Michael Murdock, her boss at the department store she worked for.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> The couple married on April 7, 1979; Baskin claims she never loved Murdock and only married him because her parents were disappointed that they had been living together outside of marriage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VE5jKxPp8tQ|title=1979 04 07|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[YouTube]]|author=Carole Baskin}}</ref> Soon after, Baskin became pregnant.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> Their daughter, Jamie Veronica Murdock, was born on July 16, 1980.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E2TT7QhWVTM|title=1980 07 16|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|author=Carole Baskin|website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> Over time, Murdock became possessive and physically abusive.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> At age nineteen, Baskin threw a [[potato]] at Murdock as he attempted to attack her and she ran out of their home barefoot.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> On that night, Baskin first met Don Lewis on Nebraska Avenue in Tampa.<ref name=\"Intel\"/><ref name=\"TheSecret\">{{Cite episode|title=The Secret|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=3|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Baskin and Lewis engaged in an affair while both were still married.<ref name=\"TheSecret\"/> The couple divorced each of their spouses and married in 1991.<ref name=\"DBeast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/joe-exotic-built-a-wild-animal-kingdom-he-was-the-most-dangerous-predator-of-them-all|title=Joe Exotic Built a Wild Animal Kingdom. He Was the Most Dangerous Predator of Them All.|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|author=Sean Williams}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Baskin and the 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', Lewis would take monthly flights to [[Costa Rica]] to deal with his [[Sexual addiction|sex addiction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxygen.com/crime-news/what-happened-to-carole-baskins-ex-husband-don-lewis-from-tiger-king|title=What Happened To Carole Baskin's Former Husband, Who Vanished In 1997?|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]]|author=Gina Tron}}</ref><ref name=\"Bible\">{{Cite web|url=https://brobible.com/culture/article/carole-baskin-boyfriend-restraining-order/|title=Carole Baskin\u2019s Boyfriend After Her Husband Disappeared Also Filed For A Chilling Restraining Order Against Her|author=Douglas Charles|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=BroBible}}</ref> According to Baskin, Lewis would time these trips for whenever she was on her [[menstrual cycle]].<ref name=\"Bible\"/> In July 1997, Lewis filed a [[restraining order]] against Baskin, claiming that Baskin had threatened to kill him; the restraining order was rejected.<ref name=DonLewisMetro>{{Cite news |title=Tiger King: Who is Carole Baskin\u2019s first husband Jack 'Don' Lewis and when did he disappear? |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326151850/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Baskin claims Lewis filed the restraining order because she would haul off some of his property whenever he visited Costa Rica.<ref name=\"Bible\"/> Lewis disappeared in August 1997.<ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office \"found no sign of foul play\" at the sanctuary and visited Costa Rica as part of their investigation.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> Lewis was [[Legal death|declared legally dead]] in 2002.<ref name= people/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/tiger-king-carole-baskin-slams-netflix-documentary/|title='Tiger King' subject Carole Baskin slams Netflix doc, calls it 'salacious and sensational'|website=EW.com}}</ref> A dispute ensued between Lewis' children and Baskin over the estate, which was mostly left to Baskin.<ref name=DonLewisMetro /> In 2011, Baskin refused to take a [[polygraph]] that was related to the investigation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-carole-baskin-don-lewis.html|title='Tiger King': What Happened to Carole Baskin\u2019s Husband, Don Lewis?|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[The New York Times]]|author=Audra D. S. Burch}}</ref> Following the ''Tiger King'' series, Hillsborough County Sheriff Chad Chronister appealed to the public for legitimate leads or evidence.<ref name=TampaSheriff>{{cite news |title=Hillsborough sheriff says tips are coming in \u2018Tiger King\u2019 missing millionaire case |author=Christopher Spata |url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/crime/2020/03/31/hillsborough-sheriff-says-tips-are-coming-in-tiger-king-missing-millionaire-case/ |website=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The case is still open as of 2020.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/police-ask-for-new-leads-in-disappearance-of-don-lewis-husband-of-tiger-king-star-carole-baskin/|title=Police ask for new leads in disappearance of Don Lewis, husband of \"Tiger King\" star Carole Baskin|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[CBS News]]}}</ref>\n\nCarole Baskin met Howard Baskin in November 2002 at a kick-off party for the newly-formed No More Homeless Pets organization.<ref name=\"Howard\">{{Cite web|url=https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin-weds-howard-baskin/|title=Carole Baskin Weds Howard Baskin|website=[[Big Cat Rescue]]|date=September 20, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330155157/https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin-weds-howard-baskin/}}</ref> Howard Baskin soon after joined Big Cat Rescue as the Chairman of the Advisory Board.<ref name=\"Howard\"/> In November 2003, Howard Baskin proposed to Carole Baskin.<ref name=\"Howard\"/> The couple married in November 2004.<ref name=\"Howard\"/>\n\n===Joe Exotic feud and ''Tiger King''===\nBaskin has a long-running feud with private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].<ref name= wrap/><ref>{{Cite episode|title=Not Your Average Joe|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=1|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Baskin had been highly critical of Exotic and his park, the [[Greater Wynnewood Exotic Animal Park]] in [[Wynnewood, Oklahoma|Wynnewood]], [[Oklahoma]], United States.<ref name= wrap/> Exotic promoted an unsubstantiated theory that Baskin was involved in the disappearance of her former husband Don Lewis.<ref name=\"CBS\"/> In 2013, a court ordered Exotic to pay Baskin [[United States dollar|$]]1 million in damages, leading to Exotic's [[bankruptcy]].<ref name=\"DBeast\"/> In 2019, Exotic was charged with planning a [[Contract killing|murder-for-hire]] against Baskin.<ref name=\"esquire\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2020/01/22/joe-exotic-zookeeper-sentencing/|title=Zookeeper who killed tigers and tried to have rival murdered is sentenced to 22 years in prison|author=Karin Brulliard|website=Washington Post|date=January 22, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123131926/https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2020/01/22/joe-exotic-zookeeper-sentencing/|archive-date=January 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBaskin was featured in ''Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness''<!--Linked above-->.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womenshealthmag.com/life/a31898876/tiger-king-carole-baskin-now/|title=Carole Baskin From Netflix's 'Tiger King' Is Doing Just Fine, TYVM|first=Korin|last=Miller|date=March 23, 2020|website=Women's Health}}</ref> She later spoke out against the series, calling it \"salacious and sensational\", and criticized directors [[Eric Goode]] and Rebecca Chaiklin.<ref name= wrap>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/tiger-king-carole-baskin-reacts-netflix-docuseries-joe-exotic/|title='Tiger King' Hitman Target Carole Baskin Shreds Netflix Docuseries: 'Salacious and Sensational'|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326001140/https://www.thewrap.com/tiger-king-carole-baskin-reacts-netflix-docuseries-joe-exotic/|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She stated that the filmmakers lied about the nature of the series. According to Baskin, when they approached her about the series they told her they were going to be making \"the big cat version of ''[[Blackfish (film)|Blackfish]]''.\"<ref name= wrap/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigcatrescue.org/refuting-netflix-tiger-king/|title=Refuting Netflix Tiger King|date=March 22, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325012206/https://bigcatrescue.org/refuting-netflix-tiger-king/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was announced in March 2020 that [[Kate McKinnon]] would portray Baskin in an upcoming scripted series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instyle.com/news/kate-mckinnon-tiger-king-carole-baskin|title=Kate McKinnon Set to Play Tiger King's Carole Baskin|website=InStyle.com|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326063733/https://www.instyle.com/news/kate-mckinnon-tiger-king-carole-baskin|archive-date=2020-03-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Animal rights|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority Control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baskin, Carole}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesswomen]]\n[[Category:Activists from Florida]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:American women chief executives]]\n[[Category:American women podcasters]]\n[[Category:Animal rights activists]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Bexar County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Zoo directors]]\n[[Category:Zoo owners]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American animal rights activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Carole Baskin\n| image              = Carole Baskin September 2019.png\n| alt                = Carole Baskin looks to her right side\n| caption            = Baskin in 2019\n| other_names        = {{hlist|Carole Stairs Jones|Carole Murdock|Carole Lewis}}\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1961|06|06}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar County]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|[[Animal sanctuary]] executive|animal rights activist}}\n| known_for          = ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness|Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness<nowiki/>]]''\n| spouse             = {{Plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Michael Murdock|1979|end=div.}}\n* {{marriage|Don Lewis|1991|2002|end=[[Legal death|legally dead]]}}\n* {{marriage|Howard Baskin|2004}}}}\n| children           = 1}}\n'''Carole Baskin''' (''[[Given name#Name at birth|n\u00e9e]]'' '''Carole Stairs Jones'''; born June 6, 1961) is an American animal rights activist and owner of [[Big Cat Rescue]], a non-profit animal sanctuary based near [[Tampa, Florida]]. Baskin drew public attention for her role in a 2020 [[Netflix]] true crime documentary limited series, ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', a series about the life-to-date of private zoo operator [[Joe Exotic]]. The Netflix series follows both Baskin and Joe Exotic, filming their ongoing and escalating feuds over [[Exotic pet|exotic animals]] in [[Zoo|private zoos]].\n\n==Early life==\nCarole was born on June 6, 1961 on the [[Lackland Air Force Base]], in [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar County]], [[Texas]], United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s1Gnw7SmYTQ|title=1961 06 06|author=Carole Baskin|date=February 26, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> At age nine, Baskin expressed an interest in saving cats but decided against pursuing a career in [[veterinarian|veterinary medicine]] after she learned that they [[Euthanasia|euthanize]] animals.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/> Baskin [[Dropping out|dropped out]] of high school and left her home at age fifteen with a local [[roller rink]] employee.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/><ref name=\"Intel\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/joe-exotic-and-his-american-animals.html|title= Joe Exotic bred lions, tigers, and ligers at his roadside zoo. He was a modern Barnum who found an equally extraordinary nemesis.|author=Robert Moor|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Intelligencer]]}}</ref> Baskin hitchhiked back-and-forth between Florida and [[Bangor, Maine|Bangor]], [[Maine]] where she would sleep under parked cars.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> Baskin later purchased an orange [[Datsun]] truck and slept in the back with her pet cat.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> Baskin returned to Florida and worked at a department store where she began a relationship with her boss Michael Murdock.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> At age seventeen, Baskin moved in with Murdock, got married, and had a daughter.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> To make money, Baskin began [[Animal breeding|breeding]] show cats.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> Baskin also began rescuing [[bobcat]]s and using [[llama]]s for a [[Lawn mower|lawn trimming]] business.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/><ref name=\"Intel\"/> Baskin later became involved in the [[real estate]] business with her second husband Don Lewis.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/>\n\n==Career==\nBaskin and her then-husband Don Lewis founded [[Big Cat Rescue]], an [[animal sanctuary]] near [[Tampa, Florida]] for [[big cat]]s, in 1992. Baskin is the current chief executive officer of Big Cat Rescue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2020-03-17/netflix-doc-who-is-carole-baskin/|title=Who is Carole Baskin? Meet the real life activist from Netflix's Tiger King|website=Radio Times}}</ref><ref name= people>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/kim-kardashian-praises-netflix-tiger-king/|title=Kim Kardashian Praises Tiger King \u2014 and Wonders if Carole Baskin Could Have Killed Her Husband|website=PEOPLE.com|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325012204/https://people.com/tv/kim-kardashian-praises-netflix-tiger-king/|archive-date=2020-03-25|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin/|title=Carole Baskin|date=March 22, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117123404/https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin/|archive-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Baskin has used social media such as [[Facebook]] and [[YouTube]] and her \"The Cat Chat\" podcast to promote her big cats activism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vengreso.com/blog/big-cat-rescue-carole-baskin|title=Big Cat Rescue\u2019s Carole Baskin|date=May 17, 2014|accessdate=March 31, 2020|author=Bernie Borges}}</ref> In March 2020, Big Cat Rescue temporarily closed to the public due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Florida|coronavirus pandemic in Florida]].<ref name=\"esquire\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a31903483/tiger-king-carole-baskin-now-alive-big-cat-rescue/|title=Carole Baskin started a Nearly Lethal Feud in 'Tiger King.' Here\u2019s Where She Is Now.|first=Gabrielle|last=Bruney|date=March 23, 2020|website=Esquire|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325192139/https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a31903483/tiger-king-carole-baskin-now-alive-big-cat-rescue/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://decider.com/2020/03/24/tiger-king-carole-baskin-where-is-she-now/|title=Who Is Carole Baskin in \u2018Tiger King\u2019 and Where Is She Now?|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325130438/https://decider.com/2020/03/24/tiger-king-carole-baskin-where-is-she-now/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Marriages===\n[[File:Tiger at Big Cat Rescue.jpg|thumb|right|A tiger at Baskin's animal sanctuary [[Big Cat Rescue]], pictured in 2012.]]\nAt age seventeen, Baskin moved in with Michael Murdock, her boss at the department store she worked for.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> The couple married on April 7, 1979; Baskin claims she never loved Murdock and only married him because her parents were disappointed that they had been living together outside of marriage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VE5jKxPp8tQ|title=1979 04 07|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[YouTube]]|author=Carole Baskin}}</ref> Soon after, Baskin became pregnant.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> Their daughter, Jamie Veronica Murdock, was born on July 16, 1980.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E2TT7QhWVTM|title=1980 07 16|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|author=Carole Baskin|website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> Over time, Murdock became possessive and physically abusive.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> At age nineteen, Baskin threw a [[potato]] at Murdock as he attempted to attack her and she ran out of their home barefoot.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> On that night, Baskin first met Don Lewis on Nebraska Avenue in Tampa.<ref name=\"Intel\"/><ref name=\"TheSecret\">{{Cite episode|title=The Secret|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=3|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Baskin and Lewis engaged in an affair while both were still married.<ref name=\"TheSecret\"/> The couple divorced each of their spouses and married in 1991.<ref name=\"DBeast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/joe-exotic-built-a-wild-animal-kingdom-he-was-the-most-dangerous-predator-of-them-all|title=Joe Exotic Built a Wild Animal Kingdom. He Was the Most Dangerous Predator of Them All.|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|author=Sean Williams}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Baskin and the 2020 crime documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', Lewis would take monthly flights to [[Costa Rica]] to deal with his [[Sexual addiction|sex addiction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxygen.com/crime-news/what-happened-to-carole-baskins-ex-husband-don-lewis-from-tiger-king|title=What Happened To Carole Baskin's Former Husband, Who Vanished In 1997?|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]]|author=Gina Tron}}</ref><ref name=\"Refute\">{{Cite web|url=https://bigcatrescue.org/refuting-netflix-tiger-king/|title=Refuting Netflix Tiger King|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[Big Cat Rescue]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330202018/https://bigcatrescue.org/refuting-netflix-tiger-king/|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Bible\">{{Cite web|url=https://brobible.com/culture/article/carole-baskin-boyfriend-restraining-order/|title=Carole Baskin\u2019s Boyfriend After Her Husband Disappeared Also Filed For A Chilling Restraining Order Against Her|author=Douglas Charles|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=BroBible}}</ref> According to Baskin, Lewis would time these trips for whenever she was on her [[menstrual cycle]].<ref name=\"Refute\"/><ref name=\"Bible\"/> In July 1997, Lewis filed a [[restraining order]] against Baskin, claiming that Baskin had threatened to kill him; the restraining order was rejected.<ref name=DonLewisMetro>{{Cite news |title=Tiger King: Who is Carole Baskin\u2019s first husband Jack 'Don' Lewis and when did he disappear? |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |website=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326151850/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Baskin claims Lewis filed the restraining order because she would haul off some of his property whenever he visited Costa Rica.<ref name=\"Refute\"/><ref name=\"Bible\"/> Lewis disappeared in August 1997.<ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office \"found no sign of foul play\" at the sanctuary and visited Costa Rica as part of their investigation.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> Lewis was [[Legal death|declared legally dead]] in 2002.<ref name= people/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/tiger-king-carole-baskin-slams-netflix-documentary/|title='Tiger King' subject Carole Baskin slams Netflix doc, calls it 'salacious and sensational'|website=EW.com}}</ref> A dispute ensued between Lewis' children and Baskin over the estate, which was mostly left to Baskin.<ref name=DonLewisMetro /> In 2011, Baskin refused to take a [[polygraph]] that was related to the investigation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-carole-baskin-don-lewis.html|title='Tiger King': What Happened to Carole Baskin\u2019s Husband, Don Lewis?|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[The New York Times]]|author=Audra D. S. Burch}}</ref> Following the ''Tiger King'' series, Hillsborough County Sheriff Chad Chronister appealed to the public for legitimate leads or evidence.<ref name=TampaSheriff>{{cite news |title=Hillsborough sheriff says tips are coming in \u2018Tiger King\u2019 missing millionaire case |author=Christopher Spata |url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/crime/2020/03/31/hillsborough-sheriff-says-tips-are-coming-in-tiger-king-missing-millionaire-case/ |website=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> The case is still open as of 2020.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/police-ask-for-new-leads-in-disappearance-of-don-lewis-husband-of-tiger-king-star-carole-baskin/|title=Police ask for new leads in disappearance of Don Lewis, husband of \"Tiger King\" star Carole Baskin|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[CBS News]]}}</ref>\n\nCarole Baskin met Howard Baskin in November 2002 at a kick-off party for the newly-formed No More Homeless Pets organization.<ref name=\"Howard\">{{Cite web|url=https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin-weds-howard-baskin/|title=Carole Baskin Weds Howard Baskin|website=[[Big Cat Rescue]]|date=September 20, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330155157/https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin-weds-howard-baskin/}}</ref> Howard Baskin soon after joined Big Cat Rescue as the Chairman of the Advisory Board.<ref name=\"Howard\"/> In November 2003, Howard Baskin proposed to Carole Baskin.<ref name=\"Howard\"/> The couple married in November 2004.<ref name=\"Howard\"/>\n\n===Joe Exotic feud and ''Tiger King''===\nBaskin has a long-running feud with private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].<ref name= wrap/><ref>{{Cite episode|title=Not Your Average Joe|series=[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]|season=1|number=1|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Baskin had been highly critical of Exotic and his park, the [[Greater Wynnewood Exotic Animal Park]] in [[Wynnewood, Oklahoma|Wynnewood]], [[Oklahoma]], United States.<ref name= wrap/> Exotic promoted an unsubstantiated theory that Baskin was involved in the disappearance of her former husband Don Lewis.<ref name=\"CBS\"/> In 2013, a court ordered Exotic to pay Baskin [[United States dollar|$]]1 million in damages, leading to Exotic's [[bankruptcy]].<ref name=\"DBeast\"/> In 2019, Exotic was charged with planning a [[Contract killing|murder-for-hire]] against Baskin.<ref name=\"esquire\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2020/01/22/joe-exotic-zookeeper-sentencing/|title=Zookeeper who killed tigers and tried to have rival murdered is sentenced to 22 years in prison|author=Karin Brulliard|website=Washington Post|date=January 22, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123131926/https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2020/01/22/joe-exotic-zookeeper-sentencing/|archive-date=January 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBaskin was featured in ''Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness''<!--Linked above-->.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womenshealthmag.com/life/a31898876/tiger-king-carole-baskin-now/|title=Carole Baskin From Netflix's 'Tiger King' Is Doing Just Fine, TYVM|first=Korin|last=Miller|date=March 23, 2020|website=Women's Health}}</ref> She later spoke out against the series, calling it \"salacious and sensational\", and criticized directors [[Eric Goode]] and Rebecca Chaiklin.<ref name= wrap>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/tiger-king-carole-baskin-reacts-netflix-docuseries-joe-exotic/|title='Tiger King' Hitman Target Carole Baskin Shreds Netflix Docuseries: 'Salacious and Sensational'|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326001140/https://www.thewrap.com/tiger-king-carole-baskin-reacts-netflix-docuseries-joe-exotic/|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She stated that the filmmakers lied about the nature of the series. According to Baskin, when they approached her about the series they told her they were going to be making \"the big cat version of ''[[Blackfish (film)|Blackfish]]''.\"<ref name= wrap/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigcatrescue.org/refuting-netflix-tiger-king/|title=Refuting Netflix Tiger King|date=March 22, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325012206/https://bigcatrescue.org/refuting-netflix-tiger-king/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was announced in March 2020 that [[Kate McKinnon]] would portray Baskin in an upcoming scripted series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instyle.com/news/kate-mckinnon-tiger-king-carole-baskin|title=Kate McKinnon Set to Play Tiger King's Carole Baskin|website=InStyle.com|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326063733/https://www.instyle.com/news/kate-mckinnon-tiger-king-carole-baskin|archive-date=2020-03-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Animal rights|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority Control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baskin, Carole}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesswomen]]\n[[Category:Activists from Florida]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:American women chief executives]]\n[[Category:American women podcasters]]\n[[Category:Animal rights activists]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Bexar County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Zoo directors]]\n[[Category:Zoo owners]]\n", "name_user": "Nice4What", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMarriages", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carole_Baskin"}
{"title_page": "Politics", "text_new": "Politics is considered to be a risky move in most south-asian countries, including India.{{pp-move|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n{{short description|Set of activities associated with the governance of a country or territory}}\n{{Politics}}\n{{other uses}}\n\n'''Politics''' is the set of activities that are associated with the [[governance]] of a [[country]], [[State (polity)|state]] or area. It involves [[making decisions]] that apply to groups of members<ref name=\"HagueHarrop2013\"/> and achieving and exercising positions of governance\u2014organized control over a human community.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/political|title=Political &#124; Definition of Political by Merriam-Webster|publisher=Merriam-webster.com|date=|accessdate=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225205552/https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/political|archive-date=25 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The academic study of politics is referred to as [[political science]].\n\nIn modern [[nation states]], people often form [[political parties]] to represent their ideas. Members of a party often agree to take the same position on many issues and agree to support the same changes to law and the same leaders.<ref>{{cite book|author=Giovanni Sartori|title=Parties and Party Systems: A Framework for Analysis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ywr0CcGDNHwC&pg=PA53|year=2005|publisher=ECPR Press|isbn=978-0-9547966-1-7|page=53|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703082251/https://books.google.com/books?id=ywr0CcGDNHwC&pg=PA53|archive-date=3 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> An [[election]] is usually a competition between different parties.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Richard Rose|author2=Neil Munro|title=Parties and Elections in New European Democracies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JfxMAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA43|date=1 April 2009|publisher=ECPR Press|isbn=978-0-9558203-2-8|page=43|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708155358/https://books.google.com/books?id=JfxMAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA43|archive-date=8 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Some examples of political parties worldwide are: the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) in [[South Africa]], the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] (D) in the [[United States]], the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in the [[United Kingdom]], the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|Christian Democratic Union]] (CDU) in [[Germany]] and the [[Indian National Congress]] in [[India]], which has the highest number of political parties in the world (2,546 political parties).<ref>{{Citation|title=List of political parties in India|date=2019-12-31|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_political_parties_in_India&oldid=933321415|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2020}}\n\nPolitics is a multifaceted word. It has a set of fairly specific meanings that are descriptive and nonjudgmental (such as \"the art or science of government\" and \"political principles\"), but does often colloquially carry a negative connotation.<ref name=\"HagueHarrop2013\">{{cite book|author1=Rod Hague|author2=Martin Harrop|title=Comparative Government and Politics: An Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IUEdBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1|date=31 May 2013|publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education|isbn=978-1-137-31786-5|pages=1\u2013|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707194650/https://books.google.com/books?id=IUEdBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1|archive-date=7 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Joseph2014\">{{cite book|author=William A. Joseph|title=Politics in China: An Introduction, Second Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v0zgAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT38|date=14 March 2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-938483-9|page=38|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702215558/https://books.google.com/books?id=v0zgAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT38|archive-date=2 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Birkland2015\">{{cite book|author=Birkland|title=Introduction to the Policy Process|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=giw8dRLqX74C&pg=PA6|date=18 May 2015|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-2731-5|page=6|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708014356/https://books.google.com/books?id=giw8dRLqX74C&pg=PA6|archive-date=8 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The word has been used negatively for many years: the [[British national anthem]] as published in 1745 calls on God to \"Confound their politics\",<ref>[[:File:Gstk.png|God save our lord the king]], ''The Gentleman's Magazine'' 15 October 1745</ref> and the phrase \"play politics\", for example, has been in use since at least 1853, when abolitionist Wendell Phillips declared: \"We do not play politics; anti-slavery is no half-jest with us.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iKyaxXvPYcQC&pg=PA233&lpg=PA233&dq=We+do+not+play+politics;+anti-slavery+is+no+half-jest+with+us#v=onepage&q=We%20do%20not%20play%20politics%3B%20anti-slavery%20is%20no%20half-jest%20with%20us&f=false|title=American Orations: V. The anti-slavery struggle|first1=Alexander|last1=Johnston|first2=James Albert|last2=Woodburn|year=1903}}</ref>\n\nA variety of methods are deployed in politics, which include promoting one's own political views among people, [[negotiation]] with other political subjects, making [[law]]s, and exercising [[force (law)|force]], including [[warfare]] against adversaries.<ref name=\"Hammarlund1985\">{{cite book|author=Bo Hammarlund|title=Politik utan partier: studier i Sveriges politiska liv 1726-1727|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BnRlAAAAIAAJ|year=1985|publisher=Almqvist & Wiksell International|page=8|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703043410/https://books.google.com/books?id=BnRlAAAAIAAJ|archive-date=3 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Brady2017\">{{cite book|author=Linda P. Brady|title=The Politics of Negotiation: America's Dealings with Allies, Adversaries, and Friends|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iNA3DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT47|date=1 October 2017|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|isbn=978-1-4696-3960-4|page=47|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702141049/https://books.google.com/books?id=iNA3DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT47|archive-date=2 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"HawkesworthKogan2013\">{{cite book|author1=Mary Hawkesworth|author2=Maurice Kogan|title=Encyclopedia of Government and Politics: 2-volume Set|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vXgKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA299|date=7 November 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-91332-7|page=299|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702181253/https://books.google.com/books?id=vXgKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA299|archive-date=2 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Taylor2012\">{{cite book|author=Steven L. Taylor|title=30-Second Politics: The 50 most thought-provoking ideas in politics, each explained in half a minute|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CV281jLqLPgC&pg=PT130|date=1 June 2012|publisher=Icon Books Limited|isbn=978-1-84831-427-6|page=130|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706214027/https://books.google.com/books?id=CV281jLqLPgC&pg=PT130|archive-date=6 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Shannon L. Blanton|author2=Charles W. Kegley|title=World Politics: Trend and Transformation, 2016\u20132017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_iVTCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA199|date=1 January 2016|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-305-50487-5|page=199|access-date=26 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702151756/https://books.google.com/books?id=_iVTCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA199|archive-date=2 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Politics is exercised on a wide range of social levels, from [[clans]] and [[tribes]] of traditional societies, through modern [[local government]]s, [[company|companies]] and institutions up to [[sovereign state]]s, to the [[international politics|international level]]. During the past decade two tendencies (1.Concern for theoretical explication and [[methodological rigor]], and 2. The emphasis on field studies of the \u201cemerging,\u201d \u201cnew,\u201d and \u201cnon-Western\u201d nations) made it possible to overlook comparative politics. <ref>{{Citation|last=Almond|first=Gabriel A.|chapter=A Developmental Approach to Political Systems|date=1986-12-31|pages=41\u201372|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-5446-2|doi=10.1515/9781400854462.41|title=Political System and Change}}</ref>\n\nA [[political system]] is a framework which defines acceptable political methods within a society. The [[history of political thought]] can be traced back to early antiquity, with seminal works such as [[Plato]]'s ''[[Republic (Plato)|Republic]]'', [[Aristotle]]'s ''[[Politics (Aristotle)|Politics]],'' the works of [[Confucius]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Political System and Change: A World Politics Reader|date=1986|publisher=Princeton University Press|jstor = j.ctt7ztn7s}}</ref> and [[Arthashastra]] and Chanakya neeti by [[Chanakya]] in 3rd Century BCE.\n\n== Etymology ==\n[[File:Women voter outreach 1935 English Yiddish.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.35|Women voter outreach from 1935]]\n\nThe word comes from the same Greek word from which the title of [[Aristotle]]'s book ''[[Politics (Aristotle)|Politics]]'' (from {{lang-grc|\u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac|''Politik\u00e1'' or ''Polis''}}, meaning \"affairs of the cities\"). The book title was rendered in [[Early Modern English]] in the mid-15th century as \"Polettiques\"<!--[sic]-->;<ref>''The Diets and Sayings of the Philosophers'' (Early English Text Society, Original Series [https://books.google.com/books?id=M7G0AAAAIAAJ&q= No. 211] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160905030633/https://books.google.com/books?id=M7G0AAAAIAAJ&q= |date=5 September 2016 }}, 1941; reprinted 1961), p. 154: \"the book of Etiques<!--[sic]--> and of Polettiques<!--[sic]-->\".</ref> it became \"politics\" in [[Modern English]]. The singular ''politic'' first attested in English 1430 and comes from [[Middle French]] ''politique'', in turn from [[Latin]] ''politicus'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0059%3Aentry%3Dpoliticus|title=A Latin Dictionary|author=Charlton T. Lewis, Charles Short|publisher=Perseus Digital Library|accessdate=19 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924204836/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0059:entry%3Dpoliticus|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> which is the [[Latinisation of names|Latinization]] of the Greek \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 (''politikos''), meaning amongst others \"of, for, or relating to citizens\", \"civil\", \"civic\", \"belonging to the state\",<ref name=\"A Greek-English Lexicon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dpolitiko%2Fs|author=Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott|title=A Greek-English Lexicon|publisher=Perseus Digital Library|accessdate=19 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924203856/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dpolitiko%2Fs|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> in turn from \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03af\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 (''polites''), \"citizen\"<ref name=\"A Greek-English Lexicon\"/> and that from \u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b9\u03c2 (''[[polis]]''), \"city\".<ref name=\"A Greek-English Lexicon\"/>\n\n===Classifications===\n'''Formal politics''' refers to the operation of a constitutional system of government and publicly defined institutions and procedures.<ref name=\"Political Geography\">{{cite web|url=http://site.ebrary.com/lib/oculyork/reader.action?docID=10870263|title=Political Geography|last1=Painter|first1=Joe|last2=Jeffrey|first2=Alex}}</ref> Political parties, public policy or discussions about war and foreign affairs would fall under the category of Formal Politics.<ref name=\"Political Geography\"/> Many people view formal politics as something outside of themselves, but that can still affect their daily lives.<ref name=\"Political Geography\"/>\n\n'''Semi-formal politics''' is politics in government associations, such as neighborhood associations, or student governments where [[Students' union|student government political party]] politics is often practiced. Student Union & Activities promotes student success by offering a variety of programs, activities, services, and facilities that, when taken together, represent a well-considered plan for the development of a school environment. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.depts.ttu.edu/sub/strategicplan.php |title=Archived copy |access-date=5 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205062033/https://www.depts.ttu.edu/sub/strategicplan.php |archive-date=5 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n'''Informal politics''' is understood as forming alliances, exercising power and protecting and advancing particular ideas or goals. Generally, this includes anything affecting one's daily life, such as the way an office or household is managed, or how one person or group exercises influence over another.<ref name=\"Political Geography\"/> Informal Politics is typically understood as everyday politics, hence the idea that \"politics is everywhere\".<ref name=\"Political Geography\"/>\n\n==History of state politics==\nThe history of politics is reflected in the origin, development, and [[economics]] of the institutions of [[government]].\n\n===The state===\n{{main article|State (polity)}}\n\nThe origin of the [[State (polity)|state]] is to be found in the development of the ''[[Ancient warfare|art of warfare]]''. Historically speaking, all political communities of the modern type owe their existence to successful warfare.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Carneiro|first=Robert L.|title=A Theory of the Origin of the State|journal=Science|date=21 August 1970|volume=169|issue=3947|doi=10.1126/science.169.3947.733|pmid=17820299|pages=733\u2013738|bibcode=1970Sci...169..733C|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/4c52e7e3539fbf4dbc163c20907e931424e91a78}}</ref>\n\nKings, emperors and other types of monarchs in many countries including China and Japan, were considered divine. Of the institutions that ruled states, that of [[kingship]] stood at the forefront until the American Revolution put an end to the \"[[divine right of kings]]\".{{citation needed|reason=I think that in the UK the establishment of parliamentary control around the glorious revolution did away with that.|date=August 2019}} Nevertheless, the monarchy is among the longest-lasting political institutions, dating as early as 2100 BC in Sumeria<ref>{{cite web|title=Sumerian King List|url=http://gizidda.altervista.org/ebooks/Sumerian-King-List-chronology.pdf|accessdate=7 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110222343/http://gizidda.altervista.org/ebooks/Sumerian-King-List-chronology.pdf|archive-date=10 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> to the 21st century AD British Monarchy. Kingship becomes an institution through the institution of [[hereditary monarchy]].\n\nThe monarch often, even in [[Monarchy|absolute monarchies]], ruled their kingdom with the aid of an elite group of advisors, a [[Privy council|council]] without which they could not maintain power. As these advisors and others outside the monarchy negotiated for power, [[constitutional monarchy|constitutional monarchies]] emerged, which may be considered the germ of [[constitutional government]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://history-world.org/absolutism.htm|work=International World History Project|title=European Absolutism And Power Politics|date=1998|accessdate=22 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512104418/http://history-world.org/absolutism.htm|archive-date=12 May 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monarchist.org.uk/constitutional-monarchy.html|title=Constitutional Monarchy|publisher=British Monarchist League Ltd|accessdate=22 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223174123/http://www.monarchist.org.uk/constitutional-monarchy.html|archive-date=23 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe greatest of the monarch's subordinates, the [[earl]]s and [[duke]]s in England and Scotland, the dukes and [[count]]s in Continental Europe, always sat as a right on the council.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} . India during the reign of the Gupta empire followed a decentralized system in which great autonomy was given to the governors of the provinces. Ancient China on the other hand followed a feudal system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.culturalindia.net/indian-history/ancient-india/ancient-government.html|title=Ancient India Government - Government In Ancient India - Law Government Ancient India|website=www.culturalindia.net|access-date=2020-01-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605221233/https://www.culturalindia.net/indian-history/ancient-india/ancient-government.html|archive-date=5 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A conqueror wages war upon the vanquished for vengeance or for plunder but an established kingdom exacts [[tribute]].{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} One of the functions of the council is to keep the [[coffers]] of the monarch full. Another is the satisfaction of [[military service]] and the establishment of [[lordship]]s by the king to satisfy the task of collecting taxes and soldiers.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jenks|first=Edward|title=A history of politics|pages=73\u201396|quote=The origin of the State, or Political Society, is to be found in the development of the art of military warfare.}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\n[[File:2017.07.26 Protest Trans Military Ban, White House, Washington DC USA 7646 (36056769341).jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.35|Activism is a form of politics.]]\n===Forms of political organization===\nThere are many forms of [[political organization]], including states, non-government organizations (NGOs) and international organizations such as the [[United Nations]]. States are perhaps the predominant institutional form of political governance, where a state is understood as an institution and a government is understood as the [[regime]] in power.\n\nAccording to Aristotle, states are classified into [[monarchies]], [[aristocracy|aristocracies]], [[Timocracy|timocracies]], [[democracies]], [[oligarchies]], and [[tyrannies]]. Due to changes across the history of politics, this classification has been abandoned.\n\nAll states are varieties of a single organizational form, the sovereign state. All the [[great powers]] of the modern world rule on the principle of [[sovereignty]]. Sovereign power may be vested on an individual as in an [[autocracy|autocratic government]] or it may be vested on a group as in a constitutional government. [[Constitutions]] are written documents that specify and limit the powers of the different branches of government. Although a constitution is a written document, there is also an unwritten constitution. The unwritten constitution is continually being written by the legislative and judiciary branch of government; this is just one of those cases in which the nature of the circumstances determines the form of government that is most appropriate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/magna-carta/articles/britains-unwritten-constitution|title=Britain's unwritten constitution|website=The British Library|access-date=2019-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401113644/https://www.bl.uk/magna-carta/articles/britains-unwritten-constitution|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> England did set the fashion of written constitutions during the [[English Civil War|Civil War]] but after the [[Restoration (England)|Restoration]] abandoned them to be taken up later by the [[American Colonies]] after their [[American Revolution|emancipation]] and then [[France]] after the [[French Revolution|Revolution]] and the rest of Europe including the European colonies.\n\nThere are many forms of government. One form is a strong central government as in France and China. Another form is local government, such as the ancient divisions in England that are comparatively weaker but less bureaucratic. These two forms helped to shape the practice of [[federal government]], first in Switzerland, then in the United States in 1776, in Canada in 1867 and in Germany in 1871 and in 1901, [[Australia]]. Federal states introduced the new principle of agreement or [[contract]]. Compared to a [[federation]], a [[confederation]] has a more dispersed system of [[judicial power]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.diffen.com/difference/Confederation_vs_Federation|title=Confederation vs Federation \u2013 Difference and Comparison|publisher=Diffen|date=|accessdate=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626030607/https://www.diffen.com/difference/Confederation_vs_Federation|archive-date=26 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[American Civil War]], the argument by the Confederate States that a State could [[secede]] from the Union was deemed unconstitutional by the [[Supreme Court of the United States|supreme court]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Texas v. White|date=1869|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?as_sdt=6&as_vis=1&case=1134912565671891096&hl=en&oi=scholarr#p726%20725|volume=74|pages=700|access-date=2019-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829054939/https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=1134912565671891096&hl=en&as_sdt=6&as_vis=1&oi=scholarr#p726%20725|archive-date=29 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to professor [[A. V. Dicey]] in ''An Introduction to the Study of the Law of the Constitution'', the essential features of a federal constitution are: a) A written supreme constitution in order to prevent disputes between the jurisdictions of the Federal and State authorities; b) A distribution of power between the Federal and State governments and c) A Supreme Court vested with the power to interpret the Constitution and enforce the law of the land remaining independent of both the executive and legislative branches.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jenks|first=Edward|title=A history of politics|url=https://archive.org/details/ahistorypolitic01jenkgoog|quote=politics history.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/ahistorypolitic01jenkgoog/page/n192 1]\u2013164|year=1900|publisher=J. M. Dent & Co.|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Global politics===\n{{main article|Global politics}}\n'''Global politics''' include different '''practices''' of political [[globalization]] in relation to questions of social power: from global patterns of governance to issues of globalizing conflict. The 20th century witnessed the outcome of two world wars and not only the rise and fall of the [[Third Reich]] but also the rise and relative fall of [[communism]]. The development of the [[atomic bomb]] gave the United States a more rapid end to its conflict in Japan in [[World War II]]. Later, the [[hydrogen bomb]] became the ultimate weapon of mass destruction.\n\nGlobal politics also concerns the rise of global and international '''organizations'''. The [[United Nations]] has served as a forum for peace in a world threatened by nuclear war, \"The invention of nuclear and space weapons has made war unacceptable as an instrument for achieving political ends.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Rabinowitch|first=Eugene|authorlink=Eugene Rabinowitch|title=Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-QsAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA13&dq=World+politics+final+nuclear+holocaust&q=World%20politics%20final%20nuclear%20holocaust|date=June 1973|page=13|issn=0096-3402|quote=...the rationale of traditional patterns of world politics.|publisher=Educational Foundation for Nuclear Science, Inc.}}</ref> Although an all-out final [[nuclear holocaust]] is radically undesirable for man, \"[[nuclear blackmail]]\" comes into question not only on the issue of world peace but also on the issue of national sovereignty.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dulles|first=Allen|authorlink=Allen Dulles|title=The Craft of Intelligence|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mH3qdHK6_EsC&pg=PA224&dq=the+craft+of+intelligence+April+1963#v=onepage&q=|page=224|year=2006|publisher=Globe Pequot|isbn=978-1-59921-577-8|quote=...using 'nuclear blackmail' as a threat to intimidate other countries.}}</ref> On a Sunday in 1962, the world stood still at the brink of nuclear war during the October [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] from the implementation of U.S. vs [[Soviet Union]] nuclear blackmail policy.{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=December 2019}}\n\nAfter the Soviet Union collapsed in December of 1991 the world moved from being bi-polar to being uni-polar with United States firmly ahead. However this lead has been continuously shrinking in the 21st Century with the rapid economic growth of China threatening the current American hegemony. Other world powers such as India and a resurgent Russia are also threatening America's position as the leader of the world. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cirsd.org/en/horizons/horizons-winter-2018-issue-no-10/great-powers-in-the-twenty-first-century|title=Great Powers in the Twenty-first Century|website=CIRSD|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[political science]] professor [[Paul James (academic)|Paul James]], global politics is affected by ''values'': norms of [[human rights]], ideas of [[human development (humanity)|human development]], and beliefs such as [[cosmopolitanism]] about how we should relate to each:\n{{quote|Cosmopolitanism can be defined as a global politics that, firstly, projects a sociality of common political engagement among all human beings across the globe, and, secondly, suggests that this sociality should be either ethically or organizationally privileged over other forms of sociality.<ref>{{cite book|year=2014|last1=James|first1=Paul|authorlink=Paul James (academic)|title=Globalization and Politics, Vol. 4: Political Philosophies of the Global|url=https://www.academia.edu/7547819|publisher=Sage Publications|location=London|pages=x|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref>}}<br />\n===Political corruption===\n{{main article|Political corruption}}\n[[William Pitt the Elder]], speaking before the British [[House of Lords]], 9 January 1770, observed: \"Unlimited power is apt to corrupt the minds of those who possess it.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Safire's Political Dictionary|editor-first=William|editor-last=Safire|date=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=566}}</ref> This was echoed more famously by [[John Dalberg-Acton]] over a century later: \"Power tends to corrupt, and absolute power corrupts absolutely.\"<ref name=\"lmcone\">Dalberg-Acton, John (Lord Acton). [http://history.hanover.edu/courses/excerpts/165acton.html Letter to Bishop Mandell Creighton, April 5, 1887] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150803083543/http://history.hanover.edu/courses/excerpts/165acton.html |date=3 August 2015 }}. Published in ''Historical Essays and Studies'', edited by J. N. Figgis and R. V. Laurence (London: Macmillan, 1907)</ref>\n\n'''Political corruption''' is the use of legislated powers by government officials for illegitimate private gain. Misuse of government power for other purposes, such as [[Political repression|repression]] of political opponents and general [[police brutality]], is not considered political corruption. Neither are illegal acts by private persons or corporations not directly involved with the government. An illegal act by an officeholder constitutes political corruption only if the act is directly related to their official duties and/or power.<ref>{{cite web|title=Political Corruption Law & Definition|url=http://definitions.uslegal.com/p/political-corruption|website=USLegal|accessdate=26 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127021554/http://definitions.uslegal.com/p/political-corruption/|archive-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The corruption in third World dictatorships is usually more blatant. For example, government cronies may be given exclusive right to make [[arbitrage]] profit by exploiting a [[fixed rate mechanism]] in government currency. In democracies corruption is often more indirect. Trade union leaders may be given priority in housing queues, giving them indirectly a worth of millions.<ref>Tino Sanadaji, ''Tio tusen miljarder: Skuldkalaset och den f\u00f6rtr\u00e4ngda baksm\u00e4llan'' (2018), kapitel 8</ref>\n\nForms of corruption vary, but include [[corruption]], [[extortion]], [[cronyism]], [[nepotism]], [[patronage]], [[Graft (politics)|graft]], and [[embezzlement]]. While corruption may facilitate [[Organized crime|criminal enterprise]] it may be legal but considered immoral.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/corruption |title=Archived copy |access-date=26 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226173233/https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/corruption |archive-date=26 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Worldwide, bribery alone is estimated to involve over 1 trillion US dollars annually.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/6288400.stm|title=African corruption 'on the wane'|publisher=BBC News \u2013 Business|access-date=7 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422141310/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/6288400.stm|archive-date=22 April 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> A state of unrestrained political corruption is known as a [[kleptocracy]], literally meaning \"rule by thieves\".<ref name=\"Wedeman2012\">{{cite book|author=Andrew Wedeman|title=Double Paradox: Rapid Growth and Rising Corruption in China|url=https://archive.org/details/doubleparadoxrap00wede|url-access=registration|date=3 April 2012|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-6474-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/doubleparadoxrap00wede/page/61 61]|access-date=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Political parties===\n{{main article|Political party}}\n\nA '''political party''' is a [[political organization]] that typically seeks to attain and maintain political power within [[government]], usually by participating in [[elections|electoral campaigns]], educational outreach or protest actions. Parties often espouse an expressed [[ideology]] or vision bolstered by a written [[Party platform|platform]] with specific goals, forming a [[coalition]] among disparate interests.<ref>{{cite book|author=Robin T. Pettitt|title=Contemporary Party Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YFYdBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA60|date=24 June 2014|publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education|isbn=978-1-137-41264-5|page=60|access-date=28 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703031727/https://books.google.com/books?id=YFYdBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA60|archive-date=3 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Politics as an academic discipline===\n[[Political science]], the study of politics, examines the acquisition and application of [[political power|power]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Safire|first=William|title=Safire's Political Dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jK-0NPoMiYoC&pg=PA566&dq=power+corrupts+and+absolute+power+corrupts+absolutely#v=onepage&q=power%20corrupts%20and%20absolute%20power%20corrupts%20absolutely|page=566|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press US|isbn=978-0-19-534334-2|quote=Power tends to corrupt; absolute power corrupts absolutely.}}</ref> Political scientist [[Harold Lasswell]] defined politics as \"who gets what, when, and how\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Schmidt|first=Barbara A.|last2=Bardes|first2=Mack C.|last3=Shelley|first3=Steffen W.|title=American Government and Politics Today: The Essentials|year=2011|publisher=Wadsworth, Cengage Learning|location=Boston|isbn=978-0-538-49719-0|edition=2011\u20132012 Student|page=[https://archive.org/details/americangovernme0000bard/page/5 5]|url=https://archive.org/details/americangovernme0000bard/page/5}}</ref> Related areas of study include [[political philosophy]], which seeks a rationale for politics and an ethic of public behaviour, as well as examining the preconditions for the formation of political communities;<ref>{{citation|title=Love's Lessons: Intimacy, Pedagogy and Political Community|first1=Timothy|last1= Laurie|first2=Hannah|last2= Stark|journal=Angelaki: Journal of the Theoretical Humanities|volume=22|issue=4|pages=69\u201379|year= 2017|url=https://www.academia.edu/35349930}}</ref> [[political economy]], which attempts to develop understandings of the relationships between politics and the economy and the governance of the two; and [[public administration]], which examines the practices of governance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/public-administration|title=Public administration - Principles of public administration|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190225181848/https://www.britannica.com/topic/public-administration|archive-date=25 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The philosopher Charles Blattberg, who has defined politics as \"responding to conflict with dialogue\", offers an account which distinguishes political philosophies from political ideologies.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Blattberg|first=Charles|title=Political Philosophies and Political Ideologies|journal=Public Affairs Quarterly|date=July 2001|volume=15|issue=3|pages=193\u2013217|ssrn=1755117|accessdate=|issn=0887-0373}}</ref>\n\nThe first academic chair devoted to politics in the United States was the chair of history and political science at [[Columbia University]], first occupied by Prussian \u00e9migr\u00e9 [[Francis Lieber]] in 1857.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Farr|first1=James|last2=Seidelman|first2=Raymond|title=Discipline and history|url=https://books.google.com/?id=e9_jbbroRHsC&pg=PA70&dq=Discipline+and+history+Francis+Lieber+Karl+Marx&q=|year=1993|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0-472-06512-7|quote=...a chair at Columbia in 1857 as professor of history and political science, the very first of its kind in America.}}</ref>\n\n==Political values==\n[[File:Political Compass yellow LibRight.svg|thumb|Two-axis political compass chart with a horizontal socio-economic axis and a vertical socio-cultural axis and ideologically representative [[political colour]]s, an example for a frequently used model of the political spectrum<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=Heywood|first=Andrew|title=Political Ideologies: An Introduction|publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education|year=2017|isbn=9781137606044|edition=6th|location=Basingstoke|pages=14\u201317|oclc=988218349}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite book|last=Love|first=Nancy Sue|title=Understanding Dogmas and Dreams|publisher=CQ Press|year=2006|isbn=9781483371115|edition=Second|location=Washington, District of Columbia|pages=16|oclc=893684473}}</ref><ref name=\":52\">{{Cite journal|last=Petrik|first=Andreas|date=2010-12-03|title=Core Concept \"Political Compass\". How Kitschelt's Model of Liberal, Socialist, Libertarian and Conservative Orientations Can Fill the Ideology Gap in Civic Education|url=http://www.jsse.org/index.php/jsse/article/view/541/538|journal=JSSE \u2013 Journal of Social Science Education|language=en|pages=4\u20132010: Social Science Literacy I: In Search for Basic Competences and Basic Concepts for Testing and Diagnosing|doi=10.4119/jsse-541}}</ref><ref name=\":62\">{{Cite journal|last=Sznajd-Weron|first=Katarzyna|last2=Sznajd|first2=J\u00f3zef|date=June 2005|title=Who is left, who is right?|journal=Physica A: Statistical Mechanics and Its Applications|language=en|volume=351|issue=2\u20134|pages=593\u2013604|bibcode=2005PhyA..351..593S|doi=10.1016/j.physa.2004.12.038}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Forman|first=F. N.|title=Mastering British Politics|last2=Baldwin|first2=N. D. J.|date=1999|publisher=Macmillan Education UK|isbn=9780333765487|location=London|pages=8 f|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-1-349-15045-8}}</ref><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite book|last=Fenna|first=Alan|title=Government Politics in Australia|last2=Robbins|first2=Jane|last3=Summers|first3=John|publisher=Pearson Higher Education AU|others=Robbins, Jane., Summers, John.|year=2013|isbn=9781486001385|edition=10th|location=Melbourne|pages=126 f|oclc=1021804010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Jones|first=Bill|title=British Politics Today|last2=Kavanagh|first2=Dennis|publisher=Manchester University Press|others=Kavanagh, Dennis.|year=2003|isbn=9780719065095|edition=7th|location=Manchester|pages=259|oclc=52876930}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=K\u00f6r\u00f6s\u00e9nyi|first=Andr\u00e1s|title=Government and Politics in Hungary|publisher=Central European University Press|year=1999|isbn=9639116769|location=Budapest, Hungary|pages=54|oclc=51478878}}</ref>]]\n[[File:3-axis-model-of-political-ideologies-with-both-moderate-and-radical-versions-and-policies-goals.png|thumb|Three axis model of political ideologies with both moderate and radical versions and the goals of their policies]]\n[[File:Inglehart Values Map.svg|thumb|upright=1.35|Political views differ on average across nations. A recreation of the [[Inglehart\u2013Welzel Cultural Map of the World]] based on the [[World Values Survey]].]]\n\n{{main article|Political spectrum}}\n\nSeveral different [[political spectrum|political spectra]] have been proposed.\n\n===Left\u2013right===\nPolitical analysts and politicians divide politics into [[left wing]] and [[right wing]] politics, often also using the idea of center politics as a middle path of policy between the right and left. This classification is comparatively recent (it was not used by [[Aristotle]] or [[Hobbes]], for instance), and dates from the [[French Revolution]] era, when those members of the [[National Assembly]] who supported the [[republic]], the common people and a [[secular society]] sat on the left and supporters of the [[monarchy]], [[aristocracy (class)|aristocratic]] privilege and the Church sat on the right.<ref name=\"Knapp\">{{cite book|author=Andrew Knapp and Vincent Wright|title=The Government and Politics of France|year=2006|publisher=Routledge}}</ref>\n\nThe meanings behind the labels have become more complicated over the years. A particularly influential event was the publication of the [[Communist Manifesto]] by [[Karl Marx]] and [[Friedrich Engels]] in 1848. The ''Manifesto'' suggested a course of action for a [[proletarian]] revolution to overthrow the [[bourgeoisie|bourgeois]] society and abolish private property, in the belief that this would lead to a [[classless]] and [[Stateless communism|stateless]] society.<ref name=\"Shepard2009\">{{cite book|author=Jon M. Shepard|title=Cengage Advantage Books: Sociology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FzefFQ-WMlYC&pg=PA214|date=12 January 2009|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-0-495-59901-2|page=214|access-date=28 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712025632/https://books.google.com/books?id=FzefFQ-WMlYC&pg=PA214|archive-date=12 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/communistmanifes00marx_5|url-access=registration|title=The Communist Manifesto|last=Marx|first=Karl|last2=Engels|first2=Friedrich|date=2002-01-01|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-0-14-044757-6|language=en|access-date=7 September 2016}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nThe meaning of left-wing and right-wing varies considerably between different countries and at different times, but generally speaking, it can be said that the right wing often values [[tradition]] and [[social stratification|inequality]] while the left wing often values [[Social progress|progress]] and [[egalitarianism]], with the center seeking a balance between the two such as with [[social democracy]], [[libertarianism]] or [[Regulated market|regulated capitalism]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-3045000932.html#C|author=Daniel J. Levinson|title=Conservatism and Radicalism|encyclopedia=International Encyclopedia of the Social Sciences|accessdate=19 February 2016|date=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160211133655/http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-3045000932.html#C|archivedate=11 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Norberto Bobbio]], one of the major exponents of this distinction, the Left believes in attempting to eradicate social inequality \u2013 believing it to be unethical or unnatural<ref>{{Cite book|title=Anarchy Works|last=Gelderloos|first=Peter|publisher=|year=2010|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> while the Right regards most social inequality as the result of ineradicable natural inequalities, and sees attempts to enforce social equality as utopian or authoritarian.<ref name=\"Bobbio\">[[Norberto Bobbio|Bobbio]], Norberto, ''Left and Right: The Significance of a Political Distinction'' (translated by Allan Cameron), 1997, [[University of Chicago Press]]. {{ISBN|0-226-06246-5}}</ref>\nSome ideologies, notably [[Christian Democracy]], claim to combine left and right wing politics; according to Geoffrey K. Roberts and Patricia Hogwood, \"In terms of ideology, Christian Democracy has incorporated many of the views held by liberals, conservatives and socialists within a wider framework of moral and Christian principles.\"<ref>Roberts and Hogwood, ''European Politics Today'', [[Manchester University Press]], 1997</ref> Movements which claim or formerly claimed to be above the left-right divide include [[Fascist]] [[Terza Posizione]] economic politics in Italy and [[Peronism]] in Argentina.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Terror from the Extreme Right.|last=Tore.|first=Bjorgo|date=2014|publisher=Taylor and Francis|isbn=9781135209308|location=Hoboken|oclc=871861016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.miis.edu/media/view/18971/original/balenouvelleresarticle.pdf|title=bale p.40|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330043520/https://www.miis.edu/media/view/18971/original/balenouvelleresarticle.pdf|archive-date=30 March 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-02-25}}</ref>\n\n===Authoritarian\u2013libertarian===\n[[Authoritarianism]] and [[civil libertarianism|libertarianism]] refer to the amount of individual [[Freedom (political)|freedom]] each person possesses in that society relative to the state. One author describes authoritarian political systems as those where \"individual [[rights]] and goals are subjugated to group goals, expectations and conformities\",<ref>{{cite journal|author=Markus Kemmelmeier|authorlink=Markus Kemmelmeier|title=Individualism, Collectivism, and Authoritarianism in Seven Societies|year=2003|journal=Journal of Cross-Cultural Psychology|volume=34|issue=3|pages=304\u2013322|doi=10.1177/0022022103034003005|display-authors=1|last2=Burnstein|first2=Eugene|last3=Krumov|first3=Krum|last4=Genkova|first4=Petia|last5=Kanagawa|first5=Chie|last6=Hirshberg|first6=Matthew S.|last7=Erb|first7=Hans-Peter|last8=Wieczorkowska|first8=Grazyna|last9=Noels|first9=Kimberly A.}}</ref> while libertarians generally oppose the [[Sovereign state|state]] and hold the [[individual]] as sovereign. In their purest form, libertarians are [[anarchism|anarchists]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://anarchism.pageabode.com/afaq/150-years-of-libertarian|title=150 years of Libertarian|author=afaq|website=Anarchists Writers|access-date=25 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925141951/http://anarchism.pageabode.com/afaq/150-years-of-libertarian|archive-date=25 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>, who argue for the total abolition of the state, of [[political parties]] and of [[Political organisation|other political entities]], while the purest authoritarians are, by definition, [[totalitarianism|totalitarians]] who support state control over all aspects of society. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dictionary.com/browse/totalitarian?s=t |title=Dictionary.com |access-date=25 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925142146/https://www.dictionary.com/browse/totalitarian?s=t |archive-date=25 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFor instance, [[classical liberalism]] (also known as ''[[laissez-faire]] liberalism'',<ref name=Adams>Ian Adams, ''Political Ideology Today'' (Manchester: Manchester University Press, 2001), 20.</ref>) is a doctrine stressing individual freedom and [[limited government]]. This includes the importance of human rationality, individual [[property rights]], [[free market]]s, [[natural rights]], the protection of [[civil liberties]], constitutional limitation of government, and individual freedom from restraint as exemplified in the writings of [[John Locke]], [[Adam Smith]], [[David Hume]], [[David Ricardo]], [[Voltaire]], [[Montesquieu]] and others. According to the libertarian [[Institute for Humane Studies]], \"the libertarian, or 'classical liberal,' perspective is that individual well-being, prosperity, and social harmony are fostered by 'as much liberty as possible' and 'as little government as necessary.'\"<ref>[http://www.theihs.org/about/id.1084/default.asp What Is Libertarian?], Institute for Humane Studies {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070324231417/http://www.theihs.org/about/id.1084/default.asp|date=24 March 2007}}</ref> For anarchist political philosopher [[L. Susan Brown]] \"Liberalism and [[anarchism]] are two political philosophies that are fundamentally concerned with individual [[Freedom of will|freedom]] yet differ from one another in very distinct ways. Anarchism shares with liberalism a radical commitment to individual freedom while rejecting liberalism's competitive property relations.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[[L. Susan Brown]]. ''[[The Politics of Individualism: Liberalism, Liberal Feminism, and Anarchism]]''. Black Rose Books Ltd. 1993</ref>\n\n=== Critiques of political spectrum ===\nThe critics of political spectrum criticize the uni dimensional and bi-dimensional nature of it. They also point towards its inability to incorporate other cultures. This rigidity leads to bizarre results. An example of this would be the fact that both fascist Adolf Hitler and libertarian Milton Friedman are on the \u201cfar right,\u201d yet Hitler advocated nationalism, socialism, militarism, authoritarianism, and anti-Semitism, while Milton Friedman advocated internationalism, capitalism, pacifism, civil liberties, and was himself a Jew. Another critic of political spectrum is its tendency to promote tribalism by needlessly sorting people into different groups.\n\nThere are also many alternatives to political spectrum and political compass. The popular among these being the ideological triangle i.e a way of organizing political ideology using the values of liberty, equality, and fraternity. The location of a political ideology on the triangle is a function of its preference for the three values. As one moves closer to the bottom corner, the preference for liberty increases. As one moves closer to the upper left-hand corner, the preference for equality increases. And as one moves closer to the upper right-hand corner, the preference for fraternity increases and political horseshoe i.e the '''horseshoe''' theory asserts that the far-left and the far-right, rather than being at opposite and opposing ends of a linear '''political''' continuum, closely resemble one another, analogous to the way that the opposite ends of a '''horseshoe''' are close together.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Politics}}\n{{Wikipedia books}}\n* [[Index of law articles]]\n* [[Index of politics articles]] \u2013 alphabetical list of political subjects\n* [[List of politics awards]]\n* [[List of years in politics]]\n* [[Outline of law]]\n* [[Outline of political science]] \u2013 structured list of political topics, arranged by subject area\n* [[Political lists]] \u2013 lists of political topics\n* [[Politics of present-day states]]\n* [[List of political ideologies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|year=1981|last1=Connolly|first1=William|authorlink=William E. Connolly|title=Appearance and Reality in Politics|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge}}\n* {{cite book|year=2014|last1=James|first1=Raul|authorlink=Paul James (academic)|last2=Soguk|first2=Nevzat|title=Globalization and Politics, Vol. 1: Global Political and Legal Governance|url=https://www.academia.edu/7285675|publisher=Sage Publications|location= London|accessdate=19 February 2016}}\n* Ryan, Alan: ''On Politics: A History of Political Thought from Herodotus to the Present.'' London: Allen Lane, 2012. {{ISBN|978-0-7139-9364-6}}\n\n{{Political ideologies}}\n{{Humanities}}\n\n{{Subject bar|wikt=yes|wikt-search=politics|commons=yes|n=yes|q=yes|s=yes|s-search=Category:Politics|b=yes|v=yes|d=yes|d-search=Q7163}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Politics| ]]\n[[Category:Main topic articles]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move|small=yes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n{{short description|Set of activities associated with the governance of a country or territory}}\n{{Politics}}\n{{other uses}}\n\n'''Politics''' is the set of activities that are associated with the [[governance]] of a [[country]], [[State (polity)|state]] or area. It involves [[making decisions]] that apply to groups of members<ref name=\"HagueHarrop2013\"/> and achieving and exercising positions of governance\u2014organized control over a human community.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/political|title=Political &#124; Definition of Political by Merriam-Webster|publisher=Merriam-webster.com|date=|accessdate=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225205552/https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/political|archive-date=25 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The academic study of politics is referred to as [[political science]].\n\nIn modern [[nation states]], people often form [[political parties]] to represent their ideas. Members of a party often agree to take the same position on many issues and agree to support the same changes to law and the same leaders.<ref>{{cite book|author=Giovanni Sartori|title=Parties and Party Systems: A Framework for Analysis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ywr0CcGDNHwC&pg=PA53|year=2005|publisher=ECPR Press|isbn=978-0-9547966-1-7|page=53|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703082251/https://books.google.com/books?id=ywr0CcGDNHwC&pg=PA53|archive-date=3 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> An [[election]] is usually a competition between different parties.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Richard Rose|author2=Neil Munro|title=Parties and Elections in New European Democracies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JfxMAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA43|date=1 April 2009|publisher=ECPR Press|isbn=978-0-9558203-2-8|page=43|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708155358/https://books.google.com/books?id=JfxMAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA43|archive-date=8 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Some examples of political parties worldwide are: the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) in [[South Africa]], the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] (D) in the [[United States]], the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in the [[United Kingdom]], the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|Christian Democratic Union]] (CDU) in [[Germany]] and the [[Indian National Congress]] in [[India]], which has the highest number of political parties in the world (2,546 political parties).<ref>{{Citation|title=List of political parties in India|date=2019-12-31|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_political_parties_in_India&oldid=933321415|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2020}}\n\nPolitics is a multifaceted word. It has a set of fairly specific meanings that are descriptive and nonjudgmental (such as \"the art or science of government\" and \"political principles\"), but does often colloquially carry a negative connotation.<ref name=\"HagueHarrop2013\">{{cite book|author1=Rod Hague|author2=Martin Harrop|title=Comparative Government and Politics: An Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IUEdBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1|date=31 May 2013|publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education|isbn=978-1-137-31786-5|pages=1\u2013|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707194650/https://books.google.com/books?id=IUEdBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1|archive-date=7 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Joseph2014\">{{cite book|author=William A. Joseph|title=Politics in China: An Introduction, Second Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v0zgAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT38|date=14 March 2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-938483-9|page=38|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702215558/https://books.google.com/books?id=v0zgAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT38|archive-date=2 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Birkland2015\">{{cite book|author=Birkland|title=Introduction to the Policy Process|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=giw8dRLqX74C&pg=PA6|date=18 May 2015|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-2731-5|page=6|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708014356/https://books.google.com/books?id=giw8dRLqX74C&pg=PA6|archive-date=8 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The word has been used negatively for many years: the [[British national anthem]] as published in 1745 calls on God to \"Confound their politics\",<ref>[[:File:Gstk.png|God save our lord the king]], ''The Gentleman's Magazine'' 15 October 1745</ref> and the phrase \"play politics\", for example, has been in use since at least 1853, when abolitionist Wendell Phillips declared: \"We do not play politics; anti-slavery is no half-jest with us.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iKyaxXvPYcQC&pg=PA233&lpg=PA233&dq=We+do+not+play+politics;+anti-slavery+is+no+half-jest+with+us#v=onepage&q=We%20do%20not%20play%20politics%3B%20anti-slavery%20is%20no%20half-jest%20with%20us&f=false|title=American Orations: V. The anti-slavery struggle|first1=Alexander|last1=Johnston|first2=James Albert|last2=Woodburn|year=1903}}</ref>\n\nA variety of methods are deployed in politics, which include promoting one's own political views among people, [[negotiation]] with other political subjects, making [[law]]s, and exercising [[force (law)|force]], including [[warfare]] against adversaries.<ref name=\"Hammarlund1985\">{{cite book|author=Bo Hammarlund|title=Politik utan partier: studier i Sveriges politiska liv 1726-1727|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BnRlAAAAIAAJ|year=1985|publisher=Almqvist & Wiksell International|page=8|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703043410/https://books.google.com/books?id=BnRlAAAAIAAJ|archive-date=3 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Brady2017\">{{cite book|author=Linda P. Brady|title=The Politics of Negotiation: America's Dealings with Allies, Adversaries, and Friends|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iNA3DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT47|date=1 October 2017|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|isbn=978-1-4696-3960-4|page=47|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702141049/https://books.google.com/books?id=iNA3DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT47|archive-date=2 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"HawkesworthKogan2013\">{{cite book|author1=Mary Hawkesworth|author2=Maurice Kogan|title=Encyclopedia of Government and Politics: 2-volume Set|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vXgKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA299|date=7 November 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-91332-7|page=299|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702181253/https://books.google.com/books?id=vXgKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA299|archive-date=2 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Taylor2012\">{{cite book|author=Steven L. Taylor|title=30-Second Politics: The 50 most thought-provoking ideas in politics, each explained in half a minute|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CV281jLqLPgC&pg=PT130|date=1 June 2012|publisher=Icon Books Limited|isbn=978-1-84831-427-6|page=130|access-date=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706214027/https://books.google.com/books?id=CV281jLqLPgC&pg=PT130|archive-date=6 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Shannon L. Blanton|author2=Charles W. Kegley|title=World Politics: Trend and Transformation, 2016\u20132017|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_iVTCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA199|date=1 January 2016|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-305-50487-5|page=199|access-date=26 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702151756/https://books.google.com/books?id=_iVTCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA199|archive-date=2 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Politics is exercised on a wide range of social levels, from [[clans]] and [[tribes]] of traditional societies, through modern [[local government]]s, [[company|companies]] and institutions up to [[sovereign state]]s, to the [[international politics|international level]]. During the past decade two tendencies (1.Concern for theoretical explication and [[methodological rigor]], and 2. The emphasis on field studies of the \u201cemerging,\u201d \u201cnew,\u201d and \u201cnon-Western\u201d nations) made it possible to overlook comparative politics. <ref>{{Citation|last=Almond|first=Gabriel A.|chapter=A Developmental Approach to Political Systems|date=1986-12-31|pages=41\u201372|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-5446-2|doi=10.1515/9781400854462.41|title=Political System and Change}}</ref>\n\nA [[political system]] is a framework which defines acceptable political methods within a society. The [[history of political thought]] can be traced back to early antiquity, with seminal works such as [[Plato]]'s ''[[Republic (Plato)|Republic]]'', [[Aristotle]]'s ''[[Politics (Aristotle)|Politics]],'' the works of [[Confucius]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Political System and Change: A World Politics Reader|date=1986|publisher=Princeton University Press|jstor = j.ctt7ztn7s}}</ref> and [[Arthashastra]] and Chanakya neeti by [[Chanakya]] in 3rd Century BCE.\n\n== Etymology ==\n[[File:Women voter outreach 1935 English Yiddish.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.35|Women voter outreach from 1935]]\n\nThe word comes from the same Greek word from which the title of [[Aristotle]]'s book ''[[Politics (Aristotle)|Politics]]'' (from {{lang-grc|\u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac|''Politik\u00e1'' or ''Polis''}}, meaning \"affairs of the cities\"). The book title was rendered in [[Early Modern English]] in the mid-15th century as \"Polettiques\"<!--[sic]-->;<ref>''The Diets and Sayings of the Philosophers'' (Early English Text Society, Original Series [https://books.google.com/books?id=M7G0AAAAIAAJ&q= No. 211] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160905030633/https://books.google.com/books?id=M7G0AAAAIAAJ&q= |date=5 September 2016 }}, 1941; reprinted 1961), p. 154: \"the book of Etiques<!--[sic]--> and of Polettiques<!--[sic]-->\".</ref> it became \"politics\" in [[Modern English]]. The singular ''politic'' first attested in English 1430 and comes from [[Middle French]] ''politique'', in turn from [[Latin]] ''politicus'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0059%3Aentry%3Dpoliticus|title=A Latin Dictionary|author=Charlton T. Lewis, Charles Short|publisher=Perseus Digital Library|accessdate=19 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924204836/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0059:entry%3Dpoliticus|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> which is the [[Latinisation of names|Latinization]] of the Greek \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 (''politikos''), meaning amongst others \"of, for, or relating to citizens\", \"civil\", \"civic\", \"belonging to the state\",<ref name=\"A Greek-English Lexicon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dpolitiko%2Fs|author=Henry George Liddell, Robert Scott|title=A Greek-English Lexicon|publisher=Perseus Digital Library|accessdate=19 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924203856/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dpolitiko%2Fs|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> in turn from \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03af\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 (''polites''), \"citizen\"<ref name=\"A Greek-English Lexicon\"/> and that from \u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b9\u03c2 (''[[polis]]''), \"city\".<ref name=\"A Greek-English Lexicon\"/>\n\n===Classifications===\n'''Formal politics''' refers to the operation of a constitutional system of government and publicly defined institutions and procedures.<ref name=\"Political Geography\">{{cite web|url=http://site.ebrary.com/lib/oculyork/reader.action?docID=10870263|title=Political Geography|last1=Painter|first1=Joe|last2=Jeffrey|first2=Alex}}</ref> Political parties, public policy or discussions about war and foreign affairs would fall under the category of Formal Politics.<ref name=\"Political Geography\"/> Many people view formal politics as something outside of themselves, but that can still affect their daily lives.<ref name=\"Political Geography\"/>\n\n'''Semi-formal politics''' is politics in government associations, such as neighborhood associations, or student governments where [[Students' union|student government political party]] politics is often practiced. Student Union & Activities promotes student success by offering a variety of programs, activities, services, and facilities that, when taken together, represent a well-considered plan for the development of a school environment. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.depts.ttu.edu/sub/strategicplan.php |title=Archived copy |access-date=5 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205062033/https://www.depts.ttu.edu/sub/strategicplan.php |archive-date=5 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n'''Informal politics''' is understood as forming alliances, exercising power and protecting and advancing particular ideas or goals. Generally, this includes anything affecting one's daily life, such as the way an office or household is managed, or how one person or group exercises influence over another.<ref name=\"Political Geography\"/> Informal Politics is typically understood as everyday politics, hence the idea that \"politics is everywhere\".<ref name=\"Political Geography\"/>\n\n==History of state politics==\nThe history of politics is reflected in the origin, development, and [[economics]] of the institutions of [[government]].\n\n===The state===\n{{main article|State (polity)}}\n\nThe origin of the [[State (polity)|state]] is to be found in the development of the ''[[Ancient warfare|art of warfare]]''. Historically speaking, all political communities of the modern type owe their existence to successful warfare.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Carneiro|first=Robert L.|title=A Theory of the Origin of the State|journal=Science|date=21 August 1970|volume=169|issue=3947|doi=10.1126/science.169.3947.733|pmid=17820299|pages=733\u2013738|bibcode=1970Sci...169..733C|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/4c52e7e3539fbf4dbc163c20907e931424e91a78}}</ref>\n\nKings, emperors and other types of monarchs in many countries including China and Japan, were considered divine. Of the institutions that ruled states, that of [[kingship]] stood at the forefront until the American Revolution put an end to the \"[[divine right of kings]]\".{{citation needed|reason=I think that in the UK the establishment of parliamentary control around the glorious revolution did away with that.|date=August 2019}} Nevertheless, the monarchy is among the longest-lasting political institutions, dating as early as 2100 BC in Sumeria<ref>{{cite web|title=Sumerian King List|url=http://gizidda.altervista.org/ebooks/Sumerian-King-List-chronology.pdf|accessdate=7 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110222343/http://gizidda.altervista.org/ebooks/Sumerian-King-List-chronology.pdf|archive-date=10 November 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> to the 21st century AD British Monarchy. Kingship becomes an institution through the institution of [[hereditary monarchy]].\n\nThe monarch often, even in [[Monarchy|absolute monarchies]], ruled their kingdom with the aid of an elite group of advisors, a [[Privy council|council]] without which they could not maintain power. As these advisors and others outside the monarchy negotiated for power, [[constitutional monarchy|constitutional monarchies]] emerged, which may be considered the germ of [[constitutional government]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://history-world.org/absolutism.htm|work=International World History Project|title=European Absolutism And Power Politics|date=1998|accessdate=22 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170512104418/http://history-world.org/absolutism.htm|archive-date=12 May 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monarchist.org.uk/constitutional-monarchy.html|title=Constitutional Monarchy|publisher=British Monarchist League Ltd|accessdate=22 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223174123/http://www.monarchist.org.uk/constitutional-monarchy.html|archive-date=23 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe greatest of the monarch's subordinates, the [[earl]]s and [[duke]]s in England and Scotland, the dukes and [[count]]s in Continental Europe, always sat as a right on the council.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} . India during the reign of the Gupta empire followed a decentralized system in which great autonomy was given to the governors of the provinces. Ancient China on the other hand followed a feudal system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.culturalindia.net/indian-history/ancient-india/ancient-government.html|title=Ancient India Government - Government In Ancient India - Law Government Ancient India|website=www.culturalindia.net|access-date=2020-01-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605221233/https://www.culturalindia.net/indian-history/ancient-india/ancient-government.html|archive-date=5 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A conqueror wages war upon the vanquished for vengeance or for plunder but an established kingdom exacts [[tribute]].{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} One of the functions of the council is to keep the [[coffers]] of the monarch full. Another is the satisfaction of [[military service]] and the establishment of [[lordship]]s by the king to satisfy the task of collecting taxes and soldiers.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jenks|first=Edward|title=A history of politics|pages=73\u201396|quote=The origin of the State, or Political Society, is to be found in the development of the art of military warfare.}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\n[[File:2017.07.26 Protest Trans Military Ban, White House, Washington DC USA 7646 (36056769341).jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.35|Activism is a form of politics.]]\n===Forms of political organization===\nThere are many forms of [[political organization]], including states, non-government organizations (NGOs) and international organizations such as the [[United Nations]]. States are perhaps the predominant institutional form of political governance, where a state is understood as an institution and a government is understood as the [[regime]] in power.\n\nAccording to Aristotle, states are classified into [[monarchies]], [[aristocracy|aristocracies]], [[Timocracy|timocracies]], [[democracies]], [[oligarchies]], and [[tyrannies]]. Due to changes across the history of politics, this classification has been abandoned.\n\nAll states are varieties of a single organizational form, the sovereign state. All the [[great powers]] of the modern world rule on the principle of [[sovereignty]]. Sovereign power may be vested on an individual as in an [[autocracy|autocratic government]] or it may be vested on a group as in a constitutional government. [[Constitutions]] are written documents that specify and limit the powers of the different branches of government. Although a constitution is a written document, there is also an unwritten constitution. The unwritten constitution is continually being written by the legislative and judiciary branch of government; this is just one of those cases in which the nature of the circumstances determines the form of government that is most appropriate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bl.uk/magna-carta/articles/britains-unwritten-constitution|title=Britain's unwritten constitution|website=The British Library|access-date=2019-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401113644/https://www.bl.uk/magna-carta/articles/britains-unwritten-constitution|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> England did set the fashion of written constitutions during the [[English Civil War|Civil War]] but after the [[Restoration (England)|Restoration]] abandoned them to be taken up later by the [[American Colonies]] after their [[American Revolution|emancipation]] and then [[France]] after the [[French Revolution|Revolution]] and the rest of Europe including the European colonies.\n\nThere are many forms of government. One form is a strong central government as in France and China. Another form is local government, such as the ancient divisions in England that are comparatively weaker but less bureaucratic. These two forms helped to shape the practice of [[federal government]], first in Switzerland, then in the United States in 1776, in Canada in 1867 and in Germany in 1871 and in 1901, [[Australia]]. Federal states introduced the new principle of agreement or [[contract]]. Compared to a [[federation]], a [[confederation]] has a more dispersed system of [[judicial power]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.diffen.com/difference/Confederation_vs_Federation|title=Confederation vs Federation \u2013 Difference and Comparison|publisher=Diffen|date=|accessdate=25 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180626030607/https://www.diffen.com/difference/Confederation_vs_Federation|archive-date=26 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[American Civil War]], the argument by the Confederate States that a State could [[secede]] from the Union was deemed unconstitutional by the [[Supreme Court of the United States|supreme court]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Texas v. White|date=1869|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?as_sdt=6&as_vis=1&case=1134912565671891096&hl=en&oi=scholarr#p726%20725|volume=74|pages=700|access-date=2019-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829054939/https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=1134912565671891096&hl=en&as_sdt=6&as_vis=1&oi=scholarr#p726%20725|archive-date=29 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to professor [[A. V. Dicey]] in ''An Introduction to the Study of the Law of the Constitution'', the essential features of a federal constitution are: a) A written supreme constitution in order to prevent disputes between the jurisdictions of the Federal and State authorities; b) A distribution of power between the Federal and State governments and c) A Supreme Court vested with the power to interpret the Constitution and enforce the law of the land remaining independent of both the executive and legislative branches.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jenks|first=Edward|title=A history of politics|url=https://archive.org/details/ahistorypolitic01jenkgoog|quote=politics history.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/ahistorypolitic01jenkgoog/page/n192 1]\u2013164|year=1900|publisher=J. M. Dent & Co.|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Global politics===\n{{main article|Global politics}}\n'''Global politics''' include different '''practices''' of political [[globalization]] in relation to questions of social power: from global patterns of governance to issues of globalizing conflict. The 20th century witnessed the outcome of two world wars and not only the rise and fall of the [[Third Reich]] but also the rise and relative fall of [[communism]]. The development of the [[atomic bomb]] gave the United States a more rapid end to its conflict in Japan in [[World War II]]. Later, the [[hydrogen bomb]] became the ultimate weapon of mass destruction.\n\nGlobal politics also concerns the rise of global and international '''organizations'''. The [[United Nations]] has served as a forum for peace in a world threatened by nuclear war, \"The invention of nuclear and space weapons has made war unacceptable as an instrument for achieving political ends.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Rabinowitch|first=Eugene|authorlink=Eugene Rabinowitch|title=Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-QsAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA13&dq=World+politics+final+nuclear+holocaust&q=World%20politics%20final%20nuclear%20holocaust|date=June 1973|page=13|issn=0096-3402|quote=...the rationale of traditional patterns of world politics.|publisher=Educational Foundation for Nuclear Science, Inc.}}</ref> Although an all-out final [[nuclear holocaust]] is radically undesirable for man, \"[[nuclear blackmail]]\" comes into question not only on the issue of world peace but also on the issue of national sovereignty.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dulles|first=Allen|authorlink=Allen Dulles|title=The Craft of Intelligence|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mH3qdHK6_EsC&pg=PA224&dq=the+craft+of+intelligence+April+1963#v=onepage&q=|page=224|year=2006|publisher=Globe Pequot|isbn=978-1-59921-577-8|quote=...using 'nuclear blackmail' as a threat to intimidate other countries.}}</ref> On a Sunday in 1962, the world stood still at the brink of nuclear war during the October [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] from the implementation of U.S. vs [[Soviet Union]] nuclear blackmail policy.{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=December 2019}}\n\nAfter the Soviet Union collapsed in December of 1991 the world moved from being bi-polar to being uni-polar with United States firmly ahead. However this lead has been continuously shrinking in the 21st Century with the rapid economic growth of China threatening the current American hegemony. Other world powers such as India and a resurgent Russia are also threatening America's position as the leader of the world. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cirsd.org/en/horizons/horizons-winter-2018-issue-no-10/great-powers-in-the-twenty-first-century|title=Great Powers in the Twenty-first Century|website=CIRSD|access-date=2020-01-04}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[political science]] professor [[Paul James (academic)|Paul James]], global politics is affected by ''values'': norms of [[human rights]], ideas of [[human development (humanity)|human development]], and beliefs such as [[cosmopolitanism]] about how we should relate to each:\n{{quote|Cosmopolitanism can be defined as a global politics that, firstly, projects a sociality of common political engagement among all human beings across the globe, and, secondly, suggests that this sociality should be either ethically or organizationally privileged over other forms of sociality.<ref>{{cite book|year=2014|last1=James|first1=Paul|authorlink=Paul James (academic)|title=Globalization and Politics, Vol. 4: Political Philosophies of the Global|url=https://www.academia.edu/7547819|publisher=Sage Publications|location=London|pages=x|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref>}}<br />\n===Political corruption===\n{{main article|Political corruption}}\n[[William Pitt the Elder]], speaking before the British [[House of Lords]], 9 January 1770, observed: \"Unlimited power is apt to corrupt the minds of those who possess it.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Safire's Political Dictionary|editor-first=William|editor-last=Safire|date=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=566}}</ref> This was echoed more famously by [[John Dalberg-Acton]] over a century later: \"Power tends to corrupt, and absolute power corrupts absolutely.\"<ref name=\"lmcone\">Dalberg-Acton, John (Lord Acton). [http://history.hanover.edu/courses/excerpts/165acton.html Letter to Bishop Mandell Creighton, April 5, 1887] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150803083543/http://history.hanover.edu/courses/excerpts/165acton.html |date=3 August 2015 }}. Published in ''Historical Essays and Studies'', edited by J. N. Figgis and R. V. Laurence (London: Macmillan, 1907)</ref>\n\n'''Political corruption''' is the use of legislated powers by government officials for illegitimate private gain. Misuse of government power for other purposes, such as [[Political repression|repression]] of political opponents and general [[police brutality]], is not considered political corruption. Neither are illegal acts by private persons or corporations not directly involved with the government. An illegal act by an officeholder constitutes political corruption only if the act is directly related to their official duties and/or power.<ref>{{cite web|title=Political Corruption Law & Definition|url=http://definitions.uslegal.com/p/political-corruption|website=USLegal|accessdate=26 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127021554/http://definitions.uslegal.com/p/political-corruption/|archive-date=27 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The corruption in third World dictatorships is usually more blatant. For example, government cronies may be given exclusive right to make [[arbitrage]] profit by exploiting a [[fixed rate mechanism]] in government currency. In democracies corruption is often more indirect. Trade union leaders may be given priority in housing queues, giving them indirectly a worth of millions.<ref>Tino Sanadaji, ''Tio tusen miljarder: Skuldkalaset och den f\u00f6rtr\u00e4ngda baksm\u00e4llan'' (2018), kapitel 8</ref>\n\nForms of corruption vary, but include [[corruption]], [[extortion]], [[cronyism]], [[nepotism]], [[patronage]], [[Graft (politics)|graft]], and [[embezzlement]]. While corruption may facilitate [[Organized crime|criminal enterprise]] it may be legal but considered immoral.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/corruption |title=Archived copy |access-date=26 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226173233/https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/corruption |archive-date=26 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Worldwide, bribery alone is estimated to involve over 1 trillion US dollars annually.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/6288400.stm|title=African corruption 'on the wane'|publisher=BBC News \u2013 Business|access-date=7 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090422141310/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/6288400.stm|archive-date=22 April 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> A state of unrestrained political corruption is known as a [[kleptocracy]], literally meaning \"rule by thieves\".<ref name=\"Wedeman2012\">{{cite book|author=Andrew Wedeman|title=Double Paradox: Rapid Growth and Rising Corruption in China|url=https://archive.org/details/doubleparadoxrap00wede|url-access=registration|date=3 April 2012|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-6474-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/doubleparadoxrap00wede/page/61 61]|access-date=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Political parties===\n{{main article|Political party}}\n\nA '''political party''' is a [[political organization]] that typically seeks to attain and maintain political power within [[government]], usually by participating in [[elections|electoral campaigns]], educational outreach or protest actions. Parties often espouse an expressed [[ideology]] or vision bolstered by a written [[Party platform|platform]] with specific goals, forming a [[coalition]] among disparate interests.<ref>{{cite book|author=Robin T. Pettitt|title=Contemporary Party Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YFYdBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA60|date=24 June 2014|publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education|isbn=978-1-137-41264-5|page=60|access-date=28 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703031727/https://books.google.com/books?id=YFYdBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA60|archive-date=3 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Politics as an academic discipline===\n[[Political science]], the study of politics, examines the acquisition and application of [[political power|power]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Safire|first=William|title=Safire's Political Dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jK-0NPoMiYoC&pg=PA566&dq=power+corrupts+and+absolute+power+corrupts+absolutely#v=onepage&q=power%20corrupts%20and%20absolute%20power%20corrupts%20absolutely|page=566|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press US|isbn=978-0-19-534334-2|quote=Power tends to corrupt; absolute power corrupts absolutely.}}</ref> Political scientist [[Harold Lasswell]] defined politics as \"who gets what, when, and how\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Schmidt|first=Barbara A.|last2=Bardes|first2=Mack C.|last3=Shelley|first3=Steffen W.|title=American Government and Politics Today: The Essentials|year=2011|publisher=Wadsworth, Cengage Learning|location=Boston|isbn=978-0-538-49719-0|edition=2011\u20132012 Student|page=[https://archive.org/details/americangovernme0000bard/page/5 5]|url=https://archive.org/details/americangovernme0000bard/page/5}}</ref> Related areas of study include [[political philosophy]], which seeks a rationale for politics and an ethic of public behaviour, as well as examining the preconditions for the formation of political communities;<ref>{{citation|title=Love's Lessons: Intimacy, Pedagogy and Political Community|first1=Timothy|last1= Laurie|first2=Hannah|last2= Stark|journal=Angelaki: Journal of the Theoretical Humanities|volume=22|issue=4|pages=69\u201379|year= 2017|url=https://www.academia.edu/35349930}}</ref> [[political economy]], which attempts to develop understandings of the relationships between politics and the economy and the governance of the two; and [[public administration]], which examines the practices of governance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/public-administration|title=Public administration - Principles of public administration|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190225181848/https://www.britannica.com/topic/public-administration|archive-date=25 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The philosopher Charles Blattberg, who has defined politics as \"responding to conflict with dialogue\", offers an account which distinguishes political philosophies from political ideologies.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Blattberg|first=Charles|title=Political Philosophies and Political Ideologies|journal=Public Affairs Quarterly|date=July 2001|volume=15|issue=3|pages=193\u2013217|ssrn=1755117|accessdate=|issn=0887-0373}}</ref>\n\nThe first academic chair devoted to politics in the United States was the chair of history and political science at [[Columbia University]], first occupied by Prussian \u00e9migr\u00e9 [[Francis Lieber]] in 1857.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Farr|first1=James|last2=Seidelman|first2=Raymond|title=Discipline and history|url=https://books.google.com/?id=e9_jbbroRHsC&pg=PA70&dq=Discipline+and+history+Francis+Lieber+Karl+Marx&q=|year=1993|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0-472-06512-7|quote=...a chair at Columbia in 1857 as professor of history and political science, the very first of its kind in America.}}</ref>\n\n==Political values==\n[[File:Political Compass yellow LibRight.svg|thumb|Two-axis political compass chart with a horizontal socio-economic axis and a vertical socio-cultural axis and ideologically representative [[political colour]]s, an example for a frequently used model of the political spectrum<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=Heywood|first=Andrew|title=Political Ideologies: An Introduction|publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education|year=2017|isbn=9781137606044|edition=6th|location=Basingstoke|pages=14\u201317|oclc=988218349}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite book|last=Love|first=Nancy Sue|title=Understanding Dogmas and Dreams|publisher=CQ Press|year=2006|isbn=9781483371115|edition=Second|location=Washington, District of Columbia|pages=16|oclc=893684473}}</ref><ref name=\":52\">{{Cite journal|last=Petrik|first=Andreas|date=2010-12-03|title=Core Concept \"Political Compass\". How Kitschelt's Model of Liberal, Socialist, Libertarian and Conservative Orientations Can Fill the Ideology Gap in Civic Education|url=http://www.jsse.org/index.php/jsse/article/view/541/538|journal=JSSE \u2013 Journal of Social Science Education|language=en|pages=4\u20132010: Social Science Literacy I: In Search for Basic Competences and Basic Concepts for Testing and Diagnosing|doi=10.4119/jsse-541}}</ref><ref name=\":62\">{{Cite journal|last=Sznajd-Weron|first=Katarzyna|last2=Sznajd|first2=J\u00f3zef|date=June 2005|title=Who is left, who is right?|journal=Physica A: Statistical Mechanics and Its Applications|language=en|volume=351|issue=2\u20134|pages=593\u2013604|bibcode=2005PhyA..351..593S|doi=10.1016/j.physa.2004.12.038}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Forman|first=F. N.|title=Mastering British Politics|last2=Baldwin|first2=N. D. J.|date=1999|publisher=Macmillan Education UK|isbn=9780333765487|location=London|pages=8 f|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-1-349-15045-8}}</ref><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite book|last=Fenna|first=Alan|title=Government Politics in Australia|last2=Robbins|first2=Jane|last3=Summers|first3=John|publisher=Pearson Higher Education AU|others=Robbins, Jane., Summers, John.|year=2013|isbn=9781486001385|edition=10th|location=Melbourne|pages=126 f|oclc=1021804010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Jones|first=Bill|title=British Politics Today|last2=Kavanagh|first2=Dennis|publisher=Manchester University Press|others=Kavanagh, Dennis.|year=2003|isbn=9780719065095|edition=7th|location=Manchester|pages=259|oclc=52876930}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=K\u00f6r\u00f6s\u00e9nyi|first=Andr\u00e1s|title=Government and Politics in Hungary|publisher=Central European University Press|year=1999|isbn=9639116769|location=Budapest, Hungary|pages=54|oclc=51478878}}</ref>]]\n[[File:3-axis-model-of-political-ideologies-with-both-moderate-and-radical-versions-and-policies-goals.png|thumb|Three axis model of political ideologies with both moderate and radical versions and the goals of their policies]]\n[[File:Inglehart Values Map.svg|thumb|upright=1.35|Political views differ on average across nations. A recreation of the [[Inglehart\u2013Welzel Cultural Map of the World]] based on the [[World Values Survey]].]]\n\n{{main article|Political spectrum}}\n\nSeveral different [[political spectrum|political spectra]] have been proposed.\n\n===Left\u2013right===\nPolitical analysts and politicians divide politics into [[left wing]] and [[right wing]] politics, often also using the idea of center politics as a middle path of policy between the right and left. This classification is comparatively recent (it was not used by [[Aristotle]] or [[Hobbes]], for instance), and dates from the [[French Revolution]] era, when those members of the [[National Assembly]] who supported the [[republic]], the common people and a [[secular society]] sat on the left and supporters of the [[monarchy]], [[aristocracy (class)|aristocratic]] privilege and the Church sat on the right.<ref name=\"Knapp\">{{cite book|author=Andrew Knapp and Vincent Wright|title=The Government and Politics of France|year=2006|publisher=Routledge}}</ref>\n\nThe meanings behind the labels have become more complicated over the years. A particularly influential event was the publication of the [[Communist Manifesto]] by [[Karl Marx]] and [[Friedrich Engels]] in 1848. The ''Manifesto'' suggested a course of action for a [[proletarian]] revolution to overthrow the [[bourgeoisie|bourgeois]] society and abolish private property, in the belief that this would lead to a [[classless]] and [[Stateless communism|stateless]] society.<ref name=\"Shepard2009\">{{cite book|author=Jon M. Shepard|title=Cengage Advantage Books: Sociology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FzefFQ-WMlYC&pg=PA214|date=12 January 2009|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-0-495-59901-2|page=214|access-date=28 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712025632/https://books.google.com/books?id=FzefFQ-WMlYC&pg=PA214|archive-date=12 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/communistmanifes00marx_5|url-access=registration|title=The Communist Manifesto|last=Marx|first=Karl|last2=Engels|first2=Friedrich|date=2002-01-01|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-0-14-044757-6|language=en|access-date=7 September 2016}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nThe meaning of left-wing and right-wing varies considerably between different countries and at different times, but generally speaking, it can be said that the right wing often values [[tradition]] and [[social stratification|inequality]] while the left wing often values [[Social progress|progress]] and [[egalitarianism]], with the center seeking a balance between the two such as with [[social democracy]], [[libertarianism]] or [[Regulated market|regulated capitalism]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-3045000932.html#C|author=Daniel J. Levinson|title=Conservatism and Radicalism|encyclopedia=International Encyclopedia of the Social Sciences|accessdate=19 February 2016|date=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160211133655/http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-3045000932.html#C|archivedate=11 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Norberto Bobbio]], one of the major exponents of this distinction, the Left believes in attempting to eradicate social inequality \u2013 believing it to be unethical or unnatural<ref>{{Cite book|title=Anarchy Works|last=Gelderloos|first=Peter|publisher=|year=2010|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> while the Right regards most social inequality as the result of ineradicable natural inequalities, and sees attempts to enforce social equality as utopian or authoritarian.<ref name=\"Bobbio\">[[Norberto Bobbio|Bobbio]], Norberto, ''Left and Right: The Significance of a Political Distinction'' (translated by Allan Cameron), 1997, [[University of Chicago Press]]. {{ISBN|0-226-06246-5}}</ref>\nSome ideologies, notably [[Christian Democracy]], claim to combine left and right wing politics; according to Geoffrey K. Roberts and Patricia Hogwood, \"In terms of ideology, Christian Democracy has incorporated many of the views held by liberals, conservatives and socialists within a wider framework of moral and Christian principles.\"<ref>Roberts and Hogwood, ''European Politics Today'', [[Manchester University Press]], 1997</ref> Movements which claim or formerly claimed to be above the left-right divide include [[Fascist]] [[Terza Posizione]] economic politics in Italy and [[Peronism]] in Argentina.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Terror from the Extreme Right.|last=Tore.|first=Bjorgo|date=2014|publisher=Taylor and Francis|isbn=9781135209308|location=Hoboken|oclc=871861016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.miis.edu/media/view/18971/original/balenouvelleresarticle.pdf|title=bale p.40|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330043520/https://www.miis.edu/media/view/18971/original/balenouvelleresarticle.pdf|archive-date=30 March 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=2018-02-25}}</ref>\n\n===Authoritarian\u2013libertarian===\n[[Authoritarianism]] and [[civil libertarianism|libertarianism]] refer to the amount of individual [[Freedom (political)|freedom]] each person possesses in that society relative to the state. One author describes authoritarian political systems as those where \"individual [[rights]] and goals are subjugated to group goals, expectations and conformities\",<ref>{{cite journal|author=Markus Kemmelmeier|authorlink=Markus Kemmelmeier|title=Individualism, Collectivism, and Authoritarianism in Seven Societies|year=2003|journal=Journal of Cross-Cultural Psychology|volume=34|issue=3|pages=304\u2013322|doi=10.1177/0022022103034003005|display-authors=1|last2=Burnstein|first2=Eugene|last3=Krumov|first3=Krum|last4=Genkova|first4=Petia|last5=Kanagawa|first5=Chie|last6=Hirshberg|first6=Matthew S.|last7=Erb|first7=Hans-Peter|last8=Wieczorkowska|first8=Grazyna|last9=Noels|first9=Kimberly A.}}</ref> while libertarians generally oppose the [[Sovereign state|state]] and hold the [[individual]] as sovereign. In their purest form, libertarians are [[anarchism|anarchists]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://anarchism.pageabode.com/afaq/150-years-of-libertarian|title=150 years of Libertarian|author=afaq|website=Anarchists Writers|access-date=25 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925141951/http://anarchism.pageabode.com/afaq/150-years-of-libertarian|archive-date=25 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>, who argue for the total abolition of the state, of [[political parties]] and of [[Political organisation|other political entities]], while the purest authoritarians are, by definition, [[totalitarianism|totalitarians]] who support state control over all aspects of society. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dictionary.com/browse/totalitarian?s=t |title=Dictionary.com |access-date=25 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925142146/https://www.dictionary.com/browse/totalitarian?s=t |archive-date=25 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFor instance, [[classical liberalism]] (also known as ''[[laissez-faire]] liberalism'',<ref name=Adams>Ian Adams, ''Political Ideology Today'' (Manchester: Manchester University Press, 2001), 20.</ref>) is a doctrine stressing individual freedom and [[limited government]]. This includes the importance of human rationality, individual [[property rights]], [[free market]]s, [[natural rights]], the protection of [[civil liberties]], constitutional limitation of government, and individual freedom from restraint as exemplified in the writings of [[John Locke]], [[Adam Smith]], [[David Hume]], [[David Ricardo]], [[Voltaire]], [[Montesquieu]] and others. According to the libertarian [[Institute for Humane Studies]], \"the libertarian, or 'classical liberal,' perspective is that individual well-being, prosperity, and social harmony are fostered by 'as much liberty as possible' and 'as little government as necessary.'\"<ref>[http://www.theihs.org/about/id.1084/default.asp What Is Libertarian?], Institute for Humane Studies {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070324231417/http://www.theihs.org/about/id.1084/default.asp|date=24 March 2007}}</ref> For anarchist political philosopher [[L. Susan Brown]] \"Liberalism and [[anarchism]] are two political philosophies that are fundamentally concerned with individual [[Freedom of will|freedom]] yet differ from one another in very distinct ways. Anarchism shares with liberalism a radical commitment to individual freedom while rejecting liberalism's competitive property relations.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">[[L. Susan Brown]]. ''[[The Politics of Individualism: Liberalism, Liberal Feminism, and Anarchism]]''. Black Rose Books Ltd. 1993</ref>\n\n=== Critiques of political spectrum ===\nThe critics of political spectrum criticize the uni dimensional and bi-dimensional nature of it. They also point towards its inability to incorporate other cultures. This rigidity leads to bizarre results. An example of this would be the fact that both fascist Adolf Hitler and libertarian Milton Friedman are on the \u201cfar right,\u201d yet Hitler advocated nationalism, socialism, militarism, authoritarianism, and anti-Semitism, while Milton Friedman advocated internationalism, capitalism, pacifism, civil liberties, and was himself a Jew. Another critic of political spectrum is its tendency to promote tribalism by needlessly sorting people into different groups.\n\nThere are also many alternatives to political spectrum and political compass. The popular among these being the ideological triangle i.e a way of organizing political ideology using the values of liberty, equality, and fraternity. The location of a political ideology on the triangle is a function of its preference for the three values. As one moves closer to the bottom corner, the preference for liberty increases. As one moves closer to the upper left-hand corner, the preference for equality increases. And as one moves closer to the upper right-hand corner, the preference for fraternity increases and political horseshoe i.e the '''horseshoe''' theory asserts that the far-left and the far-right, rather than being at opposite and opposing ends of a linear '''political''' continuum, closely resemble one another, analogous to the way that the opposite ends of a '''horseshoe''' are close together.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Politics}}\n{{Wikipedia books}}\n* [[Index of law articles]]\n* [[Index of politics articles]] \u2013 alphabetical list of political subjects\n* [[List of politics awards]]\n* [[List of years in politics]]\n* [[Outline of law]]\n* [[Outline of political science]] \u2013 structured list of political topics, arranged by subject area\n* [[Political lists]] \u2013 lists of political topics\n* [[Politics of present-day states]]\n* [[List of political ideologies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|year=1981|last1=Connolly|first1=William|authorlink=William E. Connolly|title=Appearance and Reality in Politics|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge}}\n* {{cite book|year=2014|last1=James|first1=Raul|authorlink=Paul James (academic)|last2=Soguk|first2=Nevzat|title=Globalization and Politics, Vol. 1: Global Political and Legal Governance|url=https://www.academia.edu/7285675|publisher=Sage Publications|location= London|accessdate=19 February 2016}}\n* Ryan, Alan: ''On Politics: A History of Political Thought from Herodotus to the Present.'' London: Allen Lane, 2012. {{ISBN|978-0-7139-9364-6}}\n\n{{Political ideologies}}\n{{Humanities}}\n\n{{Subject bar|wikt=yes|wikt-search=politics|commons=yes|n=yes|q=yes|s=yes|s-search=Category:Politics|b=yes|v=yes|d=yes|d-search=Q7163}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Politics| ]]\n[[Category:Main topic articles]]\n", "name_user": "Madhabilata singha roy", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a sentence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Politics"}
{"title_page": "The Tartars", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Tartars\n| image          = The Tartars (film).jpg\n| image size     =\n| caption        = Original [[film poster]]\n| director       = [[Richard Thorpe]]\n| producer       = [[Riccardo Gualino]]\n| writer         = Domenico Salvati<br>Sabatino Ciuffini<br>Oreste Palella<br>Gaio Frattini<br>Ambrogio Molteni<br>Julian De Kassel\n| based on       = \n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Victor Mature]]<br>[[Orson Welles]]\n| music          = [[Renzo Rossellini (composer)|Renzo Rossellini]]\n| cinematography = [[Amerigo Gengarelli]]\n| editing        = [[Maurizio Lucidi]]\n| studio         = [[Lux Film]]\n| distributor    = [[MGM]]\n| released       = 20 June 1962\n| runtime        = 83 min\n| country        = Italy\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross = \n}}\n'''''The Tartars'''''/'''''I Tartari''''' is a 1961 Italian/Yugoslavian [[international co-production]] [[Technicolor]] film directed by [[Richard Thorpe]] and starring [[Victor Mature]] and [[Orson Welles]].<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/93535%7C0/The-Tartars.html Jeff Stafford, \"The Tartars\", ''Turner Classic Monthly''] accessed 6 November 2012</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn what is now Russia, a settlement of [[Vikings]] lives in peace with both the [[Tatars]] and the [[Slavs]]. All is well until Togrul ([[Folco Lulli]]), a Tatar chief seeks the help of Oleg ([[Victor Mature]]), the chief of the Vikings to war on the Slavs in a surprise attack. Oleg refuses and the group does battle ending with Oleg killing Togrul and abducting Togrul's daughter Samia ([[Bella Cortez]]) as a hostage.\n\nTogrul's brother Burundai ([[Orson Welles]]) is furious and wishes the Viking settlement burnt to the ground. His high priest, Ciu Lang ([[Arnoldo Fo\u00e0]]), reminds Burundai that Samia is promised to the leader of the Tatars as his wife; her safety and return has a higher priority than Burundai's revenge. Burundai gets his chance to retrieve Samia when a Viking [[longship]] is attacked, resulting in the capture of Oleg's wife Helga ([[Liana Orfei]]) and her handmaidens. Burundai initially promises to treat Helga well as an exchange for Samia but tortures Helga's handmaidens to discover the strength of the Vikings. He also rapes Helga and gives her to his men for their further pleasure prior to exchanging her for Samia. Meanwhile, Samia has fallen in love with Oleg's brother Eric ([[Luciano Marin]]) and is pregnant with Eric's child.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Victor Mature]] as Oleg\n* [[Orson Welles]] as [[Boroldai|Burundai]]\n* [[Liana Orfei]] as Helga\n* [[Arnoldo Fo\u00e0]] as Ciu Lang\n* [[Luciano Marin]] as Eric\n* [[Bella Cortez]] as Samia\n* [[Furio Meniconi]] as Sigrun\n* [[Folco Lulli]] as Togrul\n\n==Production==\nFilming took place in Rome and Yugoslavia in October 1960.<ref>Diane Baker Will Co-star With Egan: Wyler's 'Not for Children', Players and Writers Assigned\nScheuer, Philip K. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] 18 Oct 1960: C9.</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nAccording to MGM records the film made a profit of $34,000.<ref name=\"Mannix\">{{Citation | title = The Eddie Mannix Ledger | publisher = Margaret Herrick Library, Center for Motion Picture Study | place = Los Angeles}}.</ref>\n\n===Critical===\nOrson Welles' enunciation has been praised while Victor Mature has been considered a miscast for not having the looks of an archetypal Viking.<ref>Hughes, p.34</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n* {{cite book|last=Hughes|first=Howard|title=Cinema Italiano - The Complete Guide From Classics To Cult|publisher=I.B.Tauris|year=2011|isbn=978-1-84885-608-0 |location=London - New York}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0056558}}\n* {{amg movie|112713}}\n* {{tcmdb title|id=92369}}\n\n{{Richard Thorpe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tartars}}\n[[Category:Italian films]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:1961 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Fictional Vikings]]\n[[Category:Films based on European myths and legends]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Richard Thorpe]]\n[[Category:Films set in Russia]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Viking Age]]\n[[Category:Lux Film films]]\n[[Category:1960s historical films]]\n[[Category:Italian historical films]]\n\n{{1960s-Italy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Tartars\n| image          = The Tartars (film).jpg\n| image size     =\n| caption        = Original [[film poster]]\n| director       = [[Richard Thorpe]]\n| producer       = [[Riccardo Gualino]]\n| writer         = Domenico Salvati<br>Sabatino Ciuffini<br>Oreste Palella<br>Gaio Frattini<br>Ambrogio Molteni<br>Julian De Kassel\n| based on       = \n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Victor Mature]]<br>[[Orson Welles]]\n| music          = [[Renzo Rossellini (composer)|Renzo Rossellini]]\n| cinematography = [[Amerigo Gengarelli]]\n| editing        = [[Maurizio Lucidi]]\n| studio         = [[Lux Film]]\n| distributor    = [[MGM]]\n| released       = 20 June 1962\n| runtime        = 83 min\n| country        = Italy\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross = \n}}\n'''''The Tartars'''''/'''''I Tartari''''' is a 1961 Italian/Yugoslavian [[international co-production]] [[Technicolor]] film directed by [[Richard Thorpe]] and starring [[Victor Mature]] and [[Orson Welles]].<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/93535%7C0/The-Tartars.html Jeff Stafford, \"The Tartars\", ''Turner Classic Monthly''] accessed 6 November 2012</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn what is now Russia, a settlement of [[Vikings]] lives in peace with both the [[Tatars]] and the [[Slavs]]. All is well until Togrul ([[Folco Lulli]]), a Tatar chief seeks the help of Oleg ([[Victor Mature]]), the chief of the Vikings to war on the Slavs in a surprise attack. Oleg refuses and the group does battle ending with Oleg killing Togrul and abducting Togrul's daughter Samia ([Bella Cortez]]) as a hostage.\n\nTogrul's brother Burundai ([[Orson Welles]]) is furious and wishes the Viking settlement burnt to the ground. His high priest, Ciu Lang ([[Arnoldo Fo\u00e0]]), reminds Burundai that Samia is promised to the leader of the Tatars as his wife; her safety and return has a higher priority than Burundai's revenge. Burundai gets his chance to retrieve Samia when a Viking [[longship]] is attacked, resulting in the capture of Oleg's wife Helga ([[Liana Orfei]]) and her handmaidens. Burundai initially promises to treat Helga well as an exchange for Samia but tortures Helga's handmaidens to discover the strength of the Vikings. He also rapes Helga and gives her to his men for their further pleasure prior to exchanging her for Samia. Meanwhile, Samia has fallen in love with Oleg's brother Eric ([[Luciano Marin]]) and is pregnant with Eric's child.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Victor Mature]] as Oleg\n* [[Orson Welles]] as [[Boroldai|Burundai]]\n* [[Liana Orfei]] as Helga\n* [[Arnoldo Fo\u00e0]] as Ciu Lang\n* [[Luciano Marin]] as Eric\n* [[Bella Cortez]] as Samia\n* [[Furio Meniconi]] as Sigrun\n* [[Folco Lulli]] as Togrul\n\n==Production==\nFilming took place in Rome and Yugoslavia in October 1960.<ref>Diane Baker Will Co-star With Egan: Wyler's 'Not for Children', Players and Writers Assigned\nScheuer, Philip K. Los Angeles Times (1923-Current File) [Los Angeles, Calif] 18 Oct 1960: C9.</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nAccording to MGM records the film made a profit of $34,000.<ref name=\"Mannix\">{{Citation | title = The Eddie Mannix Ledger | publisher = Margaret Herrick Library, Center for Motion Picture Study | place = Los Angeles}}.</ref>\n\n===Critical===\nOrson Welles' enunciation has been praised while Victor Mature has been considered a miscast for not having the looks of an archetypal Viking.<ref>Hughes, p.34</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n* {{cite book|last=Hughes|first=Howard|title=Cinema Italiano - The Complete Guide From Classics To