{"title_page": "Cumulus humilis cloud", "text_new": "{{short description|Cloud species}}\n{{Infobox Cloud\n| name = Idk\n| image location = Cumulus humilis.jpg\n| image name = \n| abbreviation = Cu\n| symbol = CL_1.png\n| genus= Cumulus (''heap'')\n| species= humilis (''humble'')\n| variety= \n| altitude_m =   500-3000\n| altitude_ft =  1,500-10,000\n| appearance = \n| precipitation = Uncommon, but it can be an indicator for development of storms within 12 to 24 hours. Can develop into [[cumulus mediocris]] or [[cumulus congestus|congestus]] clouds, both of which are frequent precipitation clouds.\n}}\n\n'''Cumulus humilis''' are [[cumuliform]] clouds with little vertical extent, common in the summer, that are often referred to as \"fair weather [[cumulus cloud|cumulus]]\". If they develop into [[cumulus mediocris]] or [[cumulus congestus]], thunderstorms could form later in the day.<ref name=Windows2Universe>{{Cite web | url=http://www.windows2universe.org/earth/Atmosphere/clouds/cumulus_humilis.html | title=Windows2Universe}}</ref>\n\nThey generally form at lower altitudes (500\u20133000 m (1,500\u201310,000&nbsp;ft)), but in hot countries or over mountainous terrain these clouds can occur at an altitude of up to {{convert|6000|m|abbr=on}}. They show no significant vertical development, indicating that the [[temperature]] in the atmosphere above them either drops off very slowly or not at all with altitude; that is, the [[adiabatic lapse rate]] is small. Cumulus humilis may be accompanied by other [[cloud]] types.\n \nAir below the cloud base can be quite turbulent due to the [[thermal]]s that formed the clouds, giving occupants of light aircraft an uncomfortable ride.<ref name=\"NOAA Turbulence Guide\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.weather.gov/source/zhu/ZHU_Training_Page/turbulence_stuff/turbulence/turbulence.htm | title=NOAA Turbulence Guide | accessdate=2018-06-03}}</ref> To avoid [[turbulence]] where such clouds are present, pilots may climb above the cloud tops. However, [[gliding|glider]] pilots actively seek out the rising air to gain altitude.\n\nThese clouds may later metamorphose into cumulus clouds when [[convection]] is intense enough,<ref name=\"World Meteorological Organization: Cumulus mediocris\">{{Cite web | url=https://cloudatlas.wmo.int/cumulus-mediocris.html | title=Cumulus mediocris | accessdate=2018-06-03}}</ref> though the presence of these types of clouds usually indicates fair weather.<ref name=\"Windows2Universe\" />\n\n== Forecasting ==\nMorning cumulus humilis clouds are signs of an unstable atmosphere. [[Cumulonimbus |Larger clouds]] or possibly thunderstorms could form throughout the day to cause bad or [[severe weather]] in the afternoon or evening. Cumulus humilis clouds are not rain clouds but could precede a storm.\n\nCumulus humilis are sometimes seen beneath [[cirrostratus]] clouds, which block some of the heat from the sun and thus create an [[Inversion (meteorology)|inversion]], causing any cumuliform clouds to flatten and become cumulus humilis. In this case, a warm front could be approaching and rain is possible for the next 12 to 24 hours.\n\nWhen cumulus humilis appear in a clear sky, they are an indicator of pleasant weather for the next several hours.\n\n==Formation==\nCumulus humilis clouds are formed by rising warm air or [[thermal]]s with ascending [[air current]]s of 2\u20135&nbsp;m/s (7\u201317&nbsp;ft/s).<ref name=\"World Meteorological Organization: Cumulus humilis\">{{Cite web | url=https://cloudatlas.wmo.int/cumulus-humilis.html | title=Cumulus humilis | accessdate=2018-06-03}}</ref> These clouds are usually very small convective clouds and usually form after a thermal reaches the [[Lifted condensation level|condensation level]]. They can develop into cumulus mediocris clouds but most often dissipate a few minutes after formation.<ref name=\"Weatherscapes: Cumulus humilis\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.weatherscapes.com/album.php?cat=clouds&subcat=cu_humilis | title=Cumulus humilis | accessdate=2014-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cumulus mediocris]]\n* [[Atmospheric convection]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070624065601/http://chitambo.com/clouds/cloudshtml/humilis.html Cumulus humilis]\n\n{{Cloud types}}\n\n[[Category:Cumulus]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cloud species}}\n{{Infobox Cloud\n| name = Cumulus humilis clouds \n| image location = Cumulus humilis.jpg\n| image name = \n| abbreviation = Cu\n| symbol = CL_1.png\n| genus= Cumulus (''heap'')\n| species= humilis (''humble'')\n| variety= \n| altitude_m =   500-3000\n| altitude_ft =  1,500-10,000\n| appearance = \n| precipitation = Uncommon, but it can be an indicator for development of storms within 12 to 24 hours. Can develop into [[cumulus mediocris]] or [[cumulus congestus|congestus]] clouds, both of which are frequent precipitation clouds.\n}}\n\n'''Cumulus humilis''' are [[cumuliform]] clouds with little vertical extent, common in the summer, that are often referred to as \"fair weather [[cumulus cloud|cumulus]]\". If they develop into [[cumulus mediocris]] or [[cumulus congestus]], thunderstorms could form later in the day.<ref name=Windows2Universe>{{Cite web | url=http://www.windows2universe.org/earth/Atmosphere/clouds/cumulus_humilis.html | title=Windows2Universe}}</ref>\n\nThey generally form at lower altitudes (500\u20133000 m (1,500\u201310,000&nbsp;ft)), but in hot countries or over mountainous terrain these clouds can occur at an altitude of up to {{convert|6000|m|abbr=on}}. They show no significant vertical development, indicating that the [[temperature]] in the atmosphere above them either drops off very slowly or not at all with altitude; that is, the [[adiabatic lapse rate]] is small. Cumulus humilis may be accompanied by other [[cloud]] types.\n \nAir below the cloud base can be quite turbulent due to the [[thermal]]s that formed the clouds, giving occupants of light aircraft an uncomfortable ride.<ref name=\"NOAA Turbulence Guide\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.weather.gov/source/zhu/ZHU_Training_Page/turbulence_stuff/turbulence/turbulence.htm | title=NOAA Turbulence Guide | accessdate=2018-06-03}}</ref> To avoid [[turbulence]] where such clouds are present, pilots may climb above the cloud tops. However, [[gliding|glider]] pilots actively seek out the rising air to gain altitude.\n\nThese clouds may later metamorphose into cumulus clouds when [[convection]] is intense enough,<ref name=\"World Meteorological Organization: Cumulus mediocris\">{{Cite web | url=https://cloudatlas.wmo.int/cumulus-mediocris.html | title=Cumulus mediocris | accessdate=2018-06-03}}</ref> though the presence of these types of clouds usually indicates fair weather.<ref name=\"Windows2Universe\" />\n\n== Forecasting ==\nMorning cumulus humilis clouds are signs of an unstable atmosphere. [[Cumulonimbus |Larger clouds]] or possibly thunderstorms could form throughout the day to cause bad or [[severe weather]] in the afternoon or evening. Cumulus humilis clouds are not rain clouds but could precede a storm.\n\nCumulus humilis are sometimes seen beneath [[cirrostratus]] clouds, which block some of the heat from the sun and thus create an [[Inversion (meteorology)|inversion]], causing any cumuliform clouds to flatten and become cumulus humilis. In this case, a warm front could be approaching and rain is possible for the next 12 to 24 hours.\n\nWhen cumulus humilis appear in a clear sky, they are an indicator of pleasant weather for the next several hours.\n\n==Formation==\nCumulus humilis clouds are formed by rising warm air or [[thermal]]s with ascending [[air current]]s of 2\u20135&nbsp;m/s (7\u201317&nbsp;ft/s).<ref name=\"World Meteorological Organization: Cumulus humilis\">{{Cite web | url=https://cloudatlas.wmo.int/cumulus-humilis.html | title=Cumulus humilis | accessdate=2018-06-03}}</ref> These clouds are usually very small convective clouds and usually form after a thermal reaches the [[Lifted condensation level|condensation level]]. They can develop into cumulus mediocris clouds but most often dissipate a few minutes after formation.<ref name=\"Weatherscapes: Cumulus humilis\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.weatherscapes.com/album.php?cat=clouds&subcat=cu_humilis | title=Cumulus humilis | accessdate=2014-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cumulus mediocris]]\n* [[Atmospheric convection]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070624065601/http://chitambo.com/clouds/cloudshtml/humilis.html Cumulus humilis]\n\n{{Cloud types}}\n\n[[Category:Cumulus]]\n", "name_user": "Mr Harry Masters", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added something", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cumulus_humilis_cloud"}
